{"title_page": "Craig Cliff", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Craig Cliff\n| embed = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1983\n| birth_place = [[Palmerston North]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation = writer\n| language = \n| nationality = New Zealand\n| alma_mater = [[Victoria University of Wellington]]\n| genre = fiction\n| notableworks = \n| awards = \n| website = \n| residence = \n}}\n\n'''Craig Cliff''' (born 1983) is a [[New Zealand]] [[short story writer]] and [[novelist]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.randomhouse.co.nz/authors/craig-cliff.aspx# |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128112627/http://www.randomhouse.co.nz/authors/craig-cliff.aspx# |archive-date=28 January 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nCraig Cliff was born in [[Palmerston North]] in 1983. He graduated from [[Victoria University of Wellington]] with an MA in Creative Writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://christchurchcitylibraries.com/Literature/People/C/CliffCraig/|title=Craig Cliff \u2013 Christchurch City Libraries|website=Christchurchcitylibraries.com|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCliff won the 2011 [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]], Best First Book for his short story collection ''A Man Melting''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/winning-authors-cry-the-beloved-father/story-e6frg8n6-1226060681344|title=Winning authors cry the beloved father|date=22 May 2011|website=Theaustralian.com.au|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis first novel, ''The Mannequin Makers'', was published in 2013. According to Sam Finnimore in ''The New Zealand Listener'', \"The Mannequin Makers lives up to its cover blurb billing Cliff as a talent to watch \u2013 it\u2019s tremendous, darkly entertaining and original from start to finish.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.listener.co.nz/culture/books/a-model-of-originality/|title=Book review: The Mannequin Makers, by Craig Cliff |website=Listener.co.nz|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref> The novel was also published in the US,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://milkweed.org/book/the-mannequin-makers|title=The Mannequin Makers|date=2017-01-26|website=Milkweed Editions|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref> UK<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.mhpbooks.com/books/melville-house-uk-the-mannequin-makers/|title=MELVILLE HOUSE UK: THE MANNEQUIN MAKERS \u00bb Melville House Books|last=Books|first=Melville House|date=June 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> and in Romanian translation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edituraunivers.ro/produs/creatorii-de-manechine/|title=Creatorii de manechine|website=Editura Univers|language=ro-RO|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\n''Nailing Down the Saint'', Cliff's second novel, was published in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguin.co.nz/books/nailing-down-the-saint-9780143773740|title=Nailing Down the Saint by Craig Cliff|website=www.penguin.co.nz|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to 2014, Cliff wrote a fortnightly column for ''The Dominion Post''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trout.auckland.ac.nz/journal/16/author.html?a=CraigCliff|title=Trout 16: Contributor details|website=Trout.auckland.ac.nz|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref> He participated in the University of Iowa's [[International Writing Program]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iwp.uiowa.edu/writers/craig-cliff|title=Craig Cliff  \u2013 The International Writing Program|website=Iwp.uiowa.edu|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Cliff was a recipient of [[Eleanor Catton]]'s Horoeka Grant. In response he wrote an essay on the rise of professional video gaming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://horoekareading.com/bellwethers-for-the-liquid-life-the-rise-of-professional-video-gaming-and-the-people-happy-to-sit-and-watch-by-craig-cliff/|title=\u2018Bellwethers for the Liquid Life: The Rise of Professional Video Gaming and the People Happy to Sit and Watch\u2019 by Craig Cliff|date=4 June 2015|website=Horoekareading.com|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref> He received the 2017 [[Robert Burns Fellowship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.otago.ac.nz/otagofellows/burns.html|title=The Robert Burns Fellowship, Otago Fellows, University of Otago, New Zealand|website=University of Otago|language=en-nz|access-date=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n===Short story collections===\n*''A Man Melting'' Vintage, 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-86979-192-6}}\n\n===Novels===\n*''The Mannequin Makers'' Vintage, 2013, {{ISBN|978-1-77553-384-9}}\n*''Nailing Down the Saint'' Vintage, 2019, {{ISBN|978-0-14377-374-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.craigcliff.com/ Author's website]\n*[http://yearofamillionwords.blogspot.com/ Author's blog]\n\n{{Robert Burns Fellowship}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cliff, Craig}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male short story writers]]\n[[Category:People from Palmerston North]]\n[[Category:Victoria University of Wellington alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:International Writing Program alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Craig Cliff\n| embed = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1983\n| birth_place = [[Palmerston North]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation = writer\n| language = \n| nationality = New Zealand\n| alma_mater = [[Victoria University of Wellington]]\n| genre = fiction\n| notableworks = \n| awards = \n| website = \n| residence = \n}}\n\n'''Craig Cliff''' (born 1983) is a [[New Zealand]] [[short story writer]] and [[novelist]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.randomhouse.co.nz/authors/craig-cliff.aspx# |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128112627/http://www.randomhouse.co.nz/authors/craig-cliff.aspx# |archive-date=28 January 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\n==Background==\nCraig Cliff was born in [[Palmerston North]] in 1983. He graduated from [[Victoria University of Wellington]] with an MA in Creative Writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://christchurchcitylibraries.com/Literature/People/C/CliffCraig/|title=Craig Cliff \u2013 Christchurch City Libraries|website=Christchurchcitylibraries.com|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCliff won the 2011 [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]], Best First Book for his short story collection ''A Man Melting''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/winning-authors-cry-the-beloved-father/story-e6frg8n6-1226060681344|title=Winning authors cry the beloved father|date=22 May 2011|website=Theaustralian.com.au|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nHis first novel, ''The Mannequin Makers'', was published in 2013. According to Sam Finnimore in ''The New Zealand Listener'', \"The Mannequin Makers lives up to its cover blurb billing Cliff as a talent to watch \u2013 it\u2019s tremendous, darkly entertaining and original from start to finish.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.listener.co.nz/culture/books/a-model-of-originality/|title=Book review: The Mannequin Makers, by Craig Cliff |website=Listener.co.nz|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref> The novel was also published in the US<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://milkweed.org/book/the-mannequin-makers|title=The Mannequin Makers|date=2017-01-26|website=Milkweed Editions|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>, UK<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.mhpbooks.com/books/melville-house-uk-the-mannequin-makers/|title=MELVILLE HOUSE UK: THE MANNEQUIN MAKERS \u00bb Melville House Books|last=Books|first=Melville House|date=June 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> and in Romanian translation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edituraunivers.ro/produs/creatorii-de-manechine/|title=Creatorii de manechine|website=Editura Univers|language=ro-RO|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\n''Nailing Down the Saint'', Cliff's second novel, was published in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguin.co.nz/books/nailing-down-the-saint-9780143773740|title=Nailing Down the Saint by Craig Cliff|website=www.penguin.co.nz|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to 2014, Cliff wrote a fortnightly column for ''The Dominion Post''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trout.auckland.ac.nz/journal/16/author.html?a=CraigCliff|title=Trout 16: Contributor details|website=Trout.auckland.ac.nz|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref> He participated in the University of Iowa's [[International Writing Program]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iwp.uiowa.edu/writers/craig-cliff|title=Craig Cliff  \u2013 The International Writing Program|website=Iwp.uiowa.edu|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Cliff was a recipient of [[Eleanor Catton]]'s Horoeka Grant. In response he wrote an essay on the rise of professional video gaming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://horoekareading.com/bellwethers-for-the-liquid-life-the-rise-of-professional-video-gaming-and-the-people-happy-to-sit-and-watch-by-craig-cliff/|title=\u2018Bellwethers for the Liquid Life: The Rise of Professional Video Gaming and the People Happy to Sit and Watch\u2019 by Craig Cliff|date=4 June 2015|website=Horoekareading.com|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref> He received the 2017 [[Robert Burns Fellowship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.otago.ac.nz/otagofellows/burns.html|title=The Robert Burns Fellowship, Otago Fellows, University of Otago, New Zealand|website=University of Otago|language=en-nz|access-date=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n===Short story collections===\n*''A Man Melting'' Vintage, 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-86979-192-6}}\n\n===Novels===\n*''The Mannequin Makers'' Vintage, 2013, {{ISBN|978-1-77553-384-9}}\n*''Nailing Down the Saint'' Vintage, 2019, {{ISBN|978-0-14377-374-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.craigcliff.com/ Author's website]\n*[http://yearofamillionwords.blogspot.com/ Author's blog]\n\n{{Robert Burns Fellowship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cliff, Craig}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male short story writers]]\n[[Category:People from Palmerston North]]\n[[Category:Victoria University of Wellington alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:International Writing Program alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Craig_Cliff"}
{"title_page": "Anil Ambani", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anil Ambani\n| image              = Anil_Ambani_Reliance.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Ambani in 2012\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1959|6|4|df=yes}}<ref name=ET>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/onetime-billionaire-says-hes-now-worth-nothing/amp_articleshow/74019910.cms|title=Anil Ambani: One-time billionaire Anil Ambani says he's now worth nothing - The Economic Times|website=economictimes.com}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]], [[Bombay State]], India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| alma_mater         = [[K.C. College]] (BSc)<br>[[University of Pennsylvania]] (MBA)\n| occupation         = Businessman\n| title              = Chairman, [[Reliance Group]]\n|net_worth = 0(February 2019)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/photos/business/my-net-worth-is-zero-anil-ambani-brother-of-asias-richest-man-1.1581161700031|title='My net worth is zero': Anil Ambani, brother of Asia's richest man|last=|first=|date=|work=Gulfnews|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Tina Ambani]]|1991}}\n| children           = 2 sons\n| parents            = [[Dhirubhai Ambani]]<br>Kokilaben Ambani\n| relations          = [[Mukesh Ambani]] (brother)\n| website            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Anil Dhirubhai Ambani''' (born 4 June 1959) is an Indian businessman. He is the chairman of [[Reliance Group]] (also known as [[Reliance ADA Group]]), which was created in July 2006 following a demerger from [[Reliance Industries Limited]]. He leads a number of stock listed corporations including [[Reliance Capital]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reliancecapital.co.in/|title=Reliance Capital|publisher=Reliance Capital|date=17 April 2014 |accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Reliance Infrastructure]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rinfra.com/|title=Reliance Infra|publisher=Reliance Infra|date=17 April 2014|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> [[Reliance Power]] and [[Reliance Communications]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcom.co.in/Rcom/personal/home/index.html|title=Reliance Communication|publisher=Reliance Communication|date=17 April 2014 |accessdate= April 17, 2014}}</ref> Ambani, once the sixth richest person in the world, declared before a UK court on February 2020 that his net worth is zero and he is bankrupt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/anil-ambani-tells-uk-court-his-net-worth-is-zero-despite-fleet-of-cars-private-jet-and-yacht/articleshow/74017394.cms}}<ref>  \n\nHis major business interests in entertainment include 44 FM radio stations, nationwide DTH business, animation studios, and several multiplex cinemas throughout India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnngo.com/mumbai/shop/ambani-sons-available-india-now-sold-out-383418|title=Ambani & Sons|publisher=CNNGO|date=12 June 2012|accessdate=16 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031051551/http://www.cnngo.com/mumbai/shop/ambani-sons-available-india-now-sold-out-383418|archive-date=31 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> After his father's death in 2002, Anil Ambani took over the reins of Reliance Group with interests in [[Telecommunication|telecom]], entertainment, financial services, power and infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2002/jul/07amb1.htm |title=The Ambani Achievements|publisher= Rediff.com|date=7 July 2002|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> Ambani is also credited with India's largest [[IPO]], that of [[Reliance Power]], which in 2008 was subscribed in less than 60 seconds, the fastest in the history of Indian capital markets to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exhibitmag.com/content/anil-ambani |title=Anil Ambani |publisher=EXHIBIT MAGAZINE |date=22 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206115041/http://www.exhibitmag.com/content/anil-ambani |archivedate=6 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Ambani made his debut in the entertainment industry with an acquisition of a majority stake in Adlabs Films, a company with interests in film processing, production, exhibition and digital cinema. The company was renamed [[Reliance MediaWorks]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reliance Cap buys 51% in Adlabs for Rs 360 crore|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2005-07-01/news/27503817_1_reliance-capital-adlabs-films-manmohan-shetty|accessdate=11 February 2015|work=The Economic Times|agency=Bennett, Coleman & Co. Ltd|date=1 July 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=The Reliance-Spielberg Deal: Anil Ambani's Next Blockbuster?|journal=Knowledge@Wharton|date=2 October 2008|volume=The Wharton School, University of Pennsylvania|url=http://knowledge.wharton.upenn.edu/article/the-reliance-spielberg-deal-anil-ambanis-next-blockbuster/|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Adlabs Films to be renamed Reliance MediaWorks|url=http://www.livemint.com/Consumer/9fjnwA2J9A7tzGItFVOWFP/Adlabs-Films-to-be-renamed-Reliance-MediaWorks.html|accessdate=11 February 2015|work=Live Mint|agency=HT Media|date=4 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 a joint venture worth US$1.2 billion with [[Steven Spielberg]]'s production company [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] cast Ambani's entertainment business on to a global platform.<ref>{{cite news|title=DreamWorks to Receive Funds From Reliance|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303815404577336502177912184|accessdate=11 February 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|agency=News Corporation|date=10 April 2012}}</ref> He has contributed to the production of a number of Spielberg films, including the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-winning [[Lincoln (2012 film)|''Lincoln'']].<ref>{{cite web|title=Reliance Entertainment [in]|url=https://www.imdb.com/company/co0336601/?ref_=ttco_co_3|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lincoln (2012) - Company credits|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0443272/companycredits?ref_=tt_dt_co|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAmbani earned his [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from [[Kishinchand Chellaram College]] and received a Master in Business Administration at the [[Wharton School|Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania]] in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wharton.upenn.edu/wp-content/uploads/125anniversaryissue/ambani.html|title=Wharton Alumni Magazine: 125 Influential People and Ideas: Anil D. Ambani|author=|date=|website=www.wharton.upenn.edu|accessdate=7 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAmbani is a [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]].<ref name=itn>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/business/india/top-10-gujarati-billionaires-3732.html?page=3|title=Top 10 Gujarati billionaires|date=2015-08-01|publisher=[[India TV News]]}}</ref> He is married to Indian actress [[Tina Munim]],<ref name=\"ThakurtaGhosh2014\">{{cite book|author1=Paranjoy Guha Thakurta|author2=Subir Ghosh|author3=Jyotirmoy Chaudhuri|title=GAS WARS: Crony Capitalism and the Ambanis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rMM3AwAAQBAJ&pg=PT4|date=30 March 2014|publisher=Paranjoy Guha Thakurta|isbn=978-81-928551-3-4}}</ref> and they have two sons, Jai Anmol Ambani and Jai Anshul Ambani.<ref name=\"dnaindia sons\">{{cite web|title = Tina Ambani got a third baby|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-tina-ambani-s-got-a-third-baby-1248852|website=dnaindia.com|date=18 April 2009}}</ref> Ambani is the younger brother of [[Mukesh Ambani]] and has two sisters, Nina Bhadrashyam Kothari and Dipti Dattaraj Salgaocar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/culture/who-we-are/biggest-secrets-of-ambani-family-in-pics-277696.html|title=Biggest secrets of Ambani family in pics|date=2015-03-18|website=indiatimes.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n* Conferred the 'Businessman of the Year 1997' award by India's leading business magazine [[Business India]], December 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/management/anil-d-ambani-vice-chairman-managing-director-reliance-104072001043_1.html |title=Businessman of the Year 1997 |newspaper=Business Standard India |date=20 July 2004 |publisher=business-standard.com|last1=Bureau |first1=Our }}</ref>\n* Voted 'the Businessman of the Year' in a poll conducted by [[The Times of India]] \u2013 TNS, December 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/finance/stocks/officerProfile?symbol=RLCM.NS&officerId=76505 |title=Reliance Communications Ltd (RLCM.NS) |publisher=in.reuters.com}}</ref>\n* Voted the 'Best role model' among business leaders in the biannual Mood of the Nation poll conducted by [[India Today|India Today magazine]], August 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nilacharal.com/enter/celeb/ambani.asp |title=Anil Ambani|publisher=nilacharal.com}}</ref>\n* Conferred 'the CEO of the Year 2004' in the [[S&P Global Platts|Platts Global Energy]] Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2004/dec/11ril3.htm |title=Anil Ambani is Platts CEO of the Year|publisher=rediff.com|accessdate=11 December 2004}}</ref>\n* Conferred 'The Entrepreneur of the Decade Award' by the Bombay Management Association, October 2002.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NVGI21s5lncC&pg=PA411&lpg=PA411&dq=anil+ambani+Conferred+'The+Entrepreneur+of+the+Decade+Award'+by+the+Bombay+Management+Association,+October+2002#v=onepage |title=Business Ethics and Corporate Governance|isbn=9788176295925|last1=Bhatia|first1=S. K.|year=2004}}</ref>\n* Awarded the First Wharton Indian Alumni Award by the [[Wharton India Economic Forum]] (WIEF) in recognition of his contribution to the establishment of Reliance as a global leader in many of its business areas, December 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-south-asian.com/dec2001/Wharton%20Economic%20Forum.htm |title=Wharton India Economic Forum|publisher=the-south-asian.com}}</ref>\n* Selected by [[Asiaweek|Asiaweek magazine]] for its list of 'Leaders of the Millennium in Business and Finance' and was introduced as the only 'new hero' in Business and Finance from India, June 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/1999/jun/07ambani.htm |title=Anil Ambani makes it to Asiaweek's hall of fame|publisher=rediff.com}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2018, India's principal opposition party, [[Indian National Congress]], accused [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] of favouring Anil Ambani's defence manufacturing company over [[Hindustan Aeronautics Limited|HAL]], a public sector enterprise, in a fighter aircraft deal worth INR 58,000 crores with French manufacturing firm [[Dassault]]. Ambani, several of whose companies are debt-ridden, has denied all charges of benefiting from crony capitalism. \n\nIn a possibly related controversy, one of his businesses partly financed a French film in which former [[President of France|French president]] [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande|Francois Hollande]]'s then-partner had acted around the same time the aircraft deal was being negotiated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/rafale-controversy-reliance-entertainment-francois-hollande-bjp-narendra-modi-india-france-5376140/ |title=Rafale row: Reliance Entertainment confirms it paid 1.4 million Euros for film by Hollande's partner through partner|date=27 September 2018|publisher=indianexpress.com}}</ref> \n\nHe gained notoriety as one of the fastest destroyers of shareholder wealth in the last 100 years with the combined group market cap declining by 90% since the formation of the [[Reliance ADA Group|Reliance ADA group]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/telecom/telecom-news/dcc-wants-trai-to-review-stand-on-spectrum-pricing-quantum/articleshow/69781027.cms|title=DCC wants TRAI to review stand on spectrum pricing, quantum|date=14 June 2019|newspaper=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/anil-ambani-falls-off-billionaire-club-equity-wealth-crashes-from-usd-42-billion-to-usd-523-million/story/356735.html|title=Anil Ambani falls off billionaire club; equity wealth crashes from $42 billion to $0.5 billion|website=www.businesstoday.in}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.relianceadagroup.com/ada/chairman.html Profile] at [[Reliance Anil Dhirubhai Ambani Group|Reliance ADAG]]\n* [https://www.forbes.com/profile/anil-ambani Profile] at [[Forbes]]\n* {{NYTtopic|people/a/anil_d_ambani}}\n* {{Guardian topic}}\n* [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/Anil-Ambani Anil Ambani]: collected news and commentary at ''[[The Times of India]]''\n\n{{Reliance Anil Dhirubhai Ambani Group}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ambani, Anil}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Ambani family|Anil]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n[[Category:Indian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Indian industrialists]]\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Mumbai alumni]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Reliance Anil Dhirubhai Ambani Group people]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in India]]\n[[Category:Former billionaires]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anil Ambani\n| image              = Anil_Ambani_Reliance.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Ambani in 2012\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1959|6|4|df=yes}}<ref name=ET>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/onetime-billionaire-says-hes-now-worth-nothing/amp_articleshow/74019910.cms|title=Anil Ambani: One-time billionaire Anil Ambani says he's now worth nothing - The Economic Times|website=economictimes.com}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]], [[Bombay State]], India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| alma_mater         = [[K.C. College]] (BSc)<br>[[University of Pennsylvania]] (MBA)\n| occupation         = Businessman\n| title              = Chairman, [[Reliance Group]]\n|net_worth = 0(February 2019)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/photos/business/my-net-worth-is-zero-anil-ambani-brother-of-asias-richest-man-1.1581161700031|title='My net worth is zero': Anil Ambani, brother of Asia's richest man|last=|first=|date=|work=Gulfnews|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Tina Ambani]]|1991}}\n| children           = 2 sons\n| parents            = [[Dhirubhai Ambani]]<br>Kokilaben Ambani\n| relations          = [[Mukesh Ambani]] (brother)\n| website            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Anil Dhirubhai Ambani''' (born 4 June 1959) is an Indian businessman. He is the chairman of [[Reliance Group]] (also known as [[Reliance ADA Group]]), which was created in July 2006 following a demerger from [[Reliance Industries Limited]]. He leads a number of stock listed corporations including [[Reliance Capital]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reliancecapital.co.in/|title=Reliance Capital|publisher=Reliance Capital|date=17 April 2014 |accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Reliance Infrastructure]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rinfra.com/|title=Reliance Infra|publisher=Reliance Infra|date=17 April 2014|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> [[Reliance Power]] and [[Reliance Communications]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcom.co.in/Rcom/personal/home/index.html|title=Reliance Communication|publisher=Reliance Communication|date=17 April 2014 |accessdate= April 17, 2014}}</ref> Ambani, once the sixth richest person in the world, as of July 2019, his net worth has fallen to $109 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/anil-ambani-falls-off-billionaire-club-equity-wealth-crashes-from-usd-42-billion-to-usd-523-million/story/356735.html|title=Anil Ambani worth crashes to 10$ Million|last=|first=|date=|work=Forbes|access-date=July 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis major business interests in entertainment include 44 FM radio stations, nationwide DTH business, animation studios, and several multiplex cinemas throughout India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnngo.com/mumbai/shop/ambani-sons-available-india-now-sold-out-383418|title=Ambani & Sons|publisher=CNNGO|date=12 June 2012|accessdate=16 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031051551/http://www.cnngo.com/mumbai/shop/ambani-sons-available-india-now-sold-out-383418|archive-date=31 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> After his father's death in 2002, Anil Ambani took over the reins of Reliance Group with interests in [[Telecommunication|telecom]], entertainment, financial services, power and infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2002/jul/07amb1.htm |title=The Ambani Achievements|publisher= Rediff.com|date=7 July 2002|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> Ambani is also credited with India's largest [[IPO]], that of [[Reliance Power]], which in 2008 was subscribed in less than 60 seconds, the fastest in the history of Indian capital markets to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exhibitmag.com/content/anil-ambani |title=Anil Ambani |publisher=EXHIBIT MAGAZINE |date=22 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206115041/http://www.exhibitmag.com/content/anil-ambani |archivedate=6 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Ambani made his debut in the entertainment industry with an acquisition of a majority stake in Adlabs Films, a company with interests in film processing, production, exhibition and digital cinema. The company was renamed [[Reliance MediaWorks]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reliance Cap buys 51% in Adlabs for Rs 360 crore|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2005-07-01/news/27503817_1_reliance-capital-adlabs-films-manmohan-shetty|accessdate=11 February 2015|work=The Economic Times|agency=Bennett, Coleman & Co. Ltd|date=1 July 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=The Reliance-Spielberg Deal: Anil Ambani's Next Blockbuster?|journal=Knowledge@Wharton|date=2 October 2008|volume=The Wharton School, University of Pennsylvania|url=http://knowledge.wharton.upenn.edu/article/the-reliance-spielberg-deal-anil-ambanis-next-blockbuster/|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Adlabs Films to be renamed Reliance MediaWorks|url=http://www.livemint.com/Consumer/9fjnwA2J9A7tzGItFVOWFP/Adlabs-Films-to-be-renamed-Reliance-MediaWorks.html|accessdate=11 February 2015|work=Live Mint|agency=HT Media|date=4 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 a joint venture worth US$1.2 billion with [[Steven Spielberg]]'s production company [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] cast Ambani's entertainment business on to a global platform.<ref>{{cite news|title=DreamWorks to Receive Funds From Reliance|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303815404577336502177912184|accessdate=11 February 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|agency=News Corporation|date=10 April 2012}}</ref> He has contributed to the production of a number of Spielberg films, including the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-winning [[Lincoln (2012 film)|''Lincoln'']].<ref>{{cite web|title=Reliance Entertainment [in]|url=https://www.imdb.com/company/co0336601/?ref_=ttco_co_3|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lincoln (2012) - Company credits|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0443272/companycredits?ref_=tt_dt_co|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAmbani earned his [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from [[Kishinchand Chellaram College]] and received a Master in Business Administration at the [[Wharton School|Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania]] in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wharton.upenn.edu/wp-content/uploads/125anniversaryissue/ambani.html|title=Wharton Alumni Magazine: 125 Influential People and Ideas: Anil D. Ambani|author=|date=|website=www.wharton.upenn.edu|accessdate=7 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAmbani is a [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]].<ref name=itn>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/business/india/top-10-gujarati-billionaires-3732.html?page=3|title=Top 10 Gujarati billionaires|date=2015-08-01|publisher=[[India TV News]]}}</ref> He is married to Indian actress [[Tina Munim]],<ref name=\"ThakurtaGhosh2014\">{{cite book|author1=Paranjoy Guha Thakurta|author2=Subir Ghosh|author3=Jyotirmoy Chaudhuri|title=GAS WARS: Crony Capitalism and the Ambanis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rMM3AwAAQBAJ&pg=PT4|date=30 March 2014|publisher=Paranjoy Guha Thakurta|isbn=978-81-928551-3-4}}</ref> and they have two sons, Jai Anmol Ambani and Jai Anshul Ambani.<ref name=\"dnaindia sons\">{{cite web|title = Tina Ambani got a third baby|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-tina-ambani-s-got-a-third-baby-1248852|website=dnaindia.com|date=18 April 2009}}</ref> Ambani is the younger brother of [[Mukesh Ambani]] and has two sisters, Nina Bhadrashyam Kothari and Dipti Dattaraj Salgaocar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/culture/who-we-are/biggest-secrets-of-ambani-family-in-pics-277696.html|title=Biggest secrets of Ambani family in pics|date=2015-03-18|website=indiatimes.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n* Conferred the 'Businessman of the Year 1997' award by India's leading business magazine [[Business India]], December 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/management/anil-d-ambani-vice-chairman-managing-director-reliance-104072001043_1.html |title=Businessman of the Year 1997 |newspaper=Business Standard India |date=20 July 2004 |publisher=business-standard.com|last1=Bureau |first1=Our }}</ref>\n* Voted 'the Businessman of the Year' in a poll conducted by [[The Times of India]] \u2013 TNS, December 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/finance/stocks/officerProfile?symbol=RLCM.NS&officerId=76505 |title=Reliance Communications Ltd (RLCM.NS) |publisher=in.reuters.com}}</ref>\n* Voted the 'Best role model' among business leaders in the biannual Mood of the Nation poll conducted by [[India Today|India Today magazine]], August 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nilacharal.com/enter/celeb/ambani.asp |title=Anil Ambani|publisher=nilacharal.com}}</ref>\n* Conferred 'the CEO of the Year 2004' in the [[S&P Global Platts|Platts Global Energy]] Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2004/dec/11ril3.htm |title=Anil Ambani is Platts CEO of the Year|publisher=rediff.com|accessdate=11 December 2004}}</ref>\n* Conferred 'The Entrepreneur of the Decade Award' by the Bombay Management Association, October 2002.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NVGI21s5lncC&pg=PA411&lpg=PA411&dq=anil+ambani+Conferred+'The+Entrepreneur+of+the+Decade+Award'+by+the+Bombay+Management+Association,+October+2002#v=onepage |title=Business Ethics and Corporate Governance|isbn=9788176295925|last1=Bhatia|first1=S. K.|year=2004}}</ref>\n* Awarded the First Wharton Indian Alumni Award by the [[Wharton India Economic Forum]] (WIEF) in recognition of his contribution to the establishment of Reliance as a global leader in many of its business areas, December 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-south-asian.com/dec2001/Wharton%20Economic%20Forum.htm |title=Wharton India Economic Forum|publisher=the-south-asian.com}}</ref>\n* Selected by [[Asiaweek|Asiaweek magazine]] for its list of 'Leaders of the Millennium in Business and Finance' and was introduced as the only 'new hero' in Business and Finance from India, June 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/1999/jun/07ambani.htm |title=Anil Ambani makes it to Asiaweek's hall of fame|publisher=rediff.com}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2018, India's principal opposition party, [[Indian National Congress]], accused [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] of favouring Anil Ambani's defence manufacturing company over [[Hindustan Aeronautics Limited|HAL]], a public sector enterprise, in a fighter aircraft deal worth INR 58,000 crores with French manufacturing firm [[Dassault]]. Ambani, several of whose companies are debt-ridden, has denied all charges of benefiting from crony capitalism. \n\nIn a possibly related controversy, one of his businesses partly financed a French film in which former [[President of France|French president]] [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande|Francois Hollande]]'s then-partner had acted around the same time the aircraft deal was being negotiated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/rafale-controversy-reliance-entertainment-francois-hollande-bjp-narendra-modi-india-france-5376140/ |title=Rafale row: Reliance Entertainment confirms it paid 1.4 million Euros for film by Hollande's partner through partner|date=27 September 2018|publisher=indianexpress.com}}</ref> \n\nHe gained notoriety as one of the fastest destroyers of shareholder wealth in the last 100 years with the combined group market cap declining by 90% since the formation of the [[Reliance ADA Group|Reliance ADA group]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/telecom/telecom-news/dcc-wants-trai-to-review-stand-on-spectrum-pricing-quantum/articleshow/69781027.cms|title=DCC wants TRAI to review stand on spectrum pricing, quantum|date=14 June 2019|newspaper=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/anil-ambani-falls-off-billionaire-club-equity-wealth-crashes-from-usd-42-billion-to-usd-523-million/story/356735.html|title=Anil Ambani falls off billionaire club; equity wealth crashes from $42 billion to $0.5 billion|website=www.businesstoday.in}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.relianceadagroup.com/ada/chairman.html Profile] at [[Reliance Anil Dhirubhai Ambani Group|Reliance ADAG]]\n* [https://www.forbes.com/profile/anil-ambani Profile] at [[Forbes]]\n* {{NYTtopic|people/a/anil_d_ambani}}\n* {{Guardian topic}}\n* [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/Anil-Ambani Anil Ambani]: collected news and commentary at ''[[The Times of India]]''\n\n{{Reliance Anil Dhirubhai Ambani Group}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ambani, Anil}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Ambani family|Anil]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n[[Category:Indian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Indian industrialists]]\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Mumbai alumni]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Reliance Anil Dhirubhai Ambani Group people]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in India]]\n[[Category:Former billionaires]]\n", "name_user": "Rickey.murrey", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anil_Ambani"}
{"title_page": "All Things Considered", "text_new": "{{short description|News program on the American network National Public Radio (NPR)}}\n{{About|the NPR news program}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox Radio Show\n | show_name    = All Things Considered\n | image        = All things considered logo.svg\n | imagesize    = 144px\n | format       = [[News]]: analysis, commentary, features, interviews, specials\n | runtime      = 135 minutes weekdays;<br>50 minutes weekends approx.\n | presenter    = [[Audie Cornish]]<br/>[[Mary Louise Kelly]]<br/>[[Ari Shapiro]]<br/>[[Ailsa Chang]]\n | home_station = [[NPR]]\n | country      = United States\n | first_aired  = {{Start date|1971|05|03|}}\n | last_aired   = present\n | website      = {{URL|https://www.npr.org/programs/all-things-considered}}\n | podcast      = [https://www.npr.org/rss/rss.php?id=2 Podcast]\n}}\n'''''All Things Considered''''' ('''''ATC''''') is the flagship news program on the American network [[National Public Radio]] (NPR). It was the first news program on NPR, premiering on May 3, 1971. It is broadcast live on NPR affiliated stations in the [[United States]], and worldwide through several different outlets, formerly including the NPR [[Berlin, Germany|Berlin]] station in [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/worldwide |title=NPR Worldwide |website=[[National Public Radio]] |accessdate=2007-03-06}}</ref> ''All Things Considered'' and ''[[Morning Edition]]'' were the [[List of most-listened-to radio programs|highest rated public radio programs in the United States]] in 2002 and 2005.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news |first=Samuel G. |last= Freedman |title={{-'}}Listener Supported' and 'NPR': All Things Considered |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/17/books/review/17FREEDMA.html?scp=1&sq=%22all%20things%20considered%22&st=cse |department=Books |type=Book review |quote=National Public Radio alone reaches more than 20 million listeners, and its daily newsmagazine shows, ''All Things Considered'' and ''Morning Edition,'' attract a larger audience than any program except Rush Limbaugh's. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=17 July 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title=NPR Programs Attract Record-Breaking Audiences Public Radio Listenership at All-Time High |url=https://www.npr.org/about/press/020319.recordbreak.html |quote=Reflective of the intense news cycle following the September 11 terrorist attacks on the U.S., NPR's newsmagazines and talk programs increased audiences across the board. From Fall 2000 to Fall 2001, Morning Edition with Bob Edwards jumped from 10.7 to 13 million listeners; All Things Considered grew from 9.8 million to nearly 11.9 million; Talk of the Nation rocketed 40.8 percent to 3 million listeners; Fresh Air with Terry Gross grew 25.4 percent to nearly 4.2 million and The Diane Rehm Show grew 38.6 percent to nearly 1.4 million. Growth in the NPR news/talk audience outpaced similar gains realized by commercial news/talk radio.|work=[[National Public Radio]] |date=19 March 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081224022041/http://www.npr.org/about/press/020319.recordbreak.html |archivedate=2008-12-24 |url-status=live}}</ref> The show combines news, analysis, commentary, interviews, and special features, and its segments vary in length and style. ATC airs weekdays from 4:00&nbsp;p.m. to 6:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|Eastern Standard Time]] (live) or [[Pacific Standard Time (North America)|Pacific Standard Time]] (recorded with some updates; in Hawaii it airs as a fully recorded program) or from 3:00&nbsp;p.m. to 5:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Standard Time (North America)|Central Standard Time]]. A weekend version of ''ATC'', ''Weekend All Things Considered'', airs on Saturdays and Sundays.\n\n==Background==\n''ATC'' programming combines news, analysis, commentary, interviews, and special features broadcast live daily from 4:00&nbsp;p.m. to 6:00&nbsp;p.m. Eastern Time (3 to 5 pm Central Time) (20:00 to 22:00 [[UTC]]), and is re-fed with updates until 10 p.m. ET (9 p.m. CT) or 7 p.m. PT (02:00 UTC). Broadcasts run about 105 minutes with local content interspersed in between to complete two hours. In 2005, ''ATC'' aired on over 560 radio stations and reached an audience of approximately 12 million listeners each weekday, making it the third most listened to radio program in the United States after ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]'' and ''[[Morning Edition]]''.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> In September 2010, ''All Things Considered'' had an [[AQH Share|average quarter-hour audience]] of 1.8 million.<ref name=shepard>{{cite web |first=Alicia C. |last=Shepard |date=17 September 2010 |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/ombudsman/2010/09/15/129883401/harry-shearer-post |title=Harry Shearer and NPR: The Big Uneasy |department=NPR Ombudsman |website=[[NPR]]}}</ref> ''ATC'' is co-hosted by [[Audie Cornish]], [[Ari Shapiro]], and [[Mary Louise Kelly]], regularly by turns.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|last2=Pedersen|first2=Erik|title='All Things Considered': NPR Taps Mary Louise Kelly As Co-Host; Kelly McEvers Stepping Down|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/all-things-considered-npr-mary-louise-kelly-co-host-kelly-mcevers-robert-siegel-1202229086/|accessdate=8 January 2018|work=Deadline|date=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe first broadcast of ''ATC'' was fed to about 90 [[radio station]]s on May 3, 1971, with host [[Robert Conley (reporter)|Robert Conley]]. During the first week, these stations were not allowed to broadcast the feed \"live\" but could record it for later broadcast. The first story was about the march on [[Washington, D.C.]] and the growing anti-[[Vietnam War protests]] taking place there.<ref>{{cite web |title=30th Anniversary Celebration of All Things Considered |url=https://www.npr.org/programs/atc/atc30/timeline/1971.html |website=[[National Public Radio]] |date=2001}}</ref> NPR chose to place its inaugural daily newscast at the afternoon commute timeslot instead of the morning because many of its affiliates at that time did not sign on for the day until mid-morning or afterward.<ref>{{cite book |title=Conflicting Communication Interests in America: the case of National Public Radio |first=Tom |last=McCourt |location=Westport, Connecticut |publisher=Praeger |date=1999 |page=45 |isbn=}}</ref> It was not until 1979, by which time most affiliates had expanded their broadcast days to begin at 6 a.m. or earlier, that NPR premiered ''[[Morning Edition]]''.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\n'''''Weekend All Things Considered''''' (''WATC'') is a one-hour version of the show that premiered in 1977,<ref>{{cite web |title=About Weekend ATC |url=http://www.wlrh.org/Schedule/programdetail.asp?ProgramID=34 |website=[[WLRH]] public radio |date=2000 |accessdate=2010-12-12}}</ref> with host Robert Conley, and is broadcast on Saturdays and Sundays at 5 p.m. ET. Michel Martin now hosts the program. Former hosts also include [[Guy Raz]]. Raz left to be the host of the ''[[TED Radio Hour]]''. On February 13, 2013, NPR announced that it was relocating production of ''WATC'' to NPR West.<ref>{{cite press release |title=NPR Relocates 'Weekend All Things Considered' to NPR West |url=https://www.npr.org/about/press/2013/021313.WATCNPRWest.html |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=13 February 2013}}</ref> Production returned to Washington, DC in 2015.\n\n''ATC'' was excluded from the NPR deal with [[Sirius Satellite Radio]] so as not to compete with local stations airing the show.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lynette |last=Clemetson |title=All Things Considered, NPR's Growing Clout Alarms Member Stations |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/30/arts/all-things-considered-npr-s-growing-clout-alarms-member-stations.html |quote=NPR has a contract to program two Sirius channels, NPR Talk and NPR Now. But Mr. Klose said there were no plans to add the top-rated news programs to its satellite lineup against station wishes. ''We will respond to the will of the system,'' he said. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=30 August 2004}}</ref>\n\nTo coordinate the choice of interview partners in cultural coverage between ''ATC'' and other NPR shows (as of 2010: ''Morning Edition'', the weekend editions, ''[[Talk of the Nation]]'', and ''[[Tell Me More]]''), NPR set up a \"[[wikt:dibs|dibs]] list\" system around 2005, whereby the first show to declare interest in a particular guest can \"reserve\" that person.<ref name=shepard/>\n\nOn March 23, 2020, ''ATC'' launched '''''The National Conversation''''', a live [[call-in show]] addressing listener questions about the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]. The program airs from 9-10 p.m. ET on weeknights.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introducing 'The National Conversation With All Things Considered' |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/20/819186570/introducing-the-national-conversation-with-all-things-considered |website=NPR.org |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\nThe format is less rigid than that of ''Morning Edition'', with a wider array of type and length of stories. The length of stories tends to be greater than ''Morning Edition'', with some stories lasting for almost 23 minutes. Certain types of personal interest stories are almost always covered within this limit; those relating to hard news or entertainment tend to last the standard three-and-a-half to four minutes.\n\nThe program begins with the familiar [[Don Voegeli]] theme song<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/programs/asc/features/atc_theme/ |title=ATC Theme: The Story |website=[[All Songs Considered]] |accessdate=2013-08-10}}</ref> under a one-minute billboard of the stories to be covered during the hour. Then the standard five-minute NPR newscast is delivered from one minute to six minutes past the hour. The newscast offers a cutaway after three minutes (at four minutes past the hour), allowing stations to cover the last 2.5 minutes with evening rush-hour news and traffic reports. For those stations that run the newscast untouched, a 30-second music bed follows instead.\n\nThe first, or \"A\" segment, begins at :06:30 after the hour. It features important news stories, although not necessarily the most important news stories of the day. Often it is here that the most significant interviews or developing stories are placed. Segment A runs 11:29 in duration, and closes out at :18 after with a two-minute station break.\n\nAt :20:35 past the hour, ''ATC'' picks back up with Segment B. This segment, which runs 8:24, features more news and analysis, and often contains lighter stories and commentary. Segment B breaks for the half-hour at :29 past. The program goes into a one-minute local break.\n\nAt the bottom of the hour, ''ATC'' resumes with a \"host return\". In the 30-second return, the host or hosts discuss what's coming up in the remaining half-hour and intro the news. This is immediately followed by a 3:30 newscast which ends at :34 after the hour, followed by a one-minute local break.\n\nSegment C kicks off at :35:35 past the hour, and runs 8:24. Long feature stories are heard here, or as many as three shorter stories or commentaries may be heard as well. Segment D occurs immediately after Segment C at :44 past the hour, and runs for four minutes. Segment D is a designated cutaway for stations to run local commentary or features in lieu of the national segment. Segment D ends at :48 after the hour, and another two-minute break ensues. Occasionally, the show will \"break format\" and place a long, 12-minute story in Segments C and D without a local cutaway.\n\nSegment E starts at :50 after, and concludes the hour. The segment runs 8:09. Unlike ''Morning Edition'', there is no set format for this segment, although usually the second hour will contain an arts, culture, or lighter news story in this segment. Other times, hard news otherwise not fitting in the program may be placed here.\n\nStations receive a preliminary rundown before each broadcast (usually a few minutes before 4:00&nbsp;p.m. Eastern) denoting the timing and placement of stories so they can schedule local content as appropriate. This rundown is updated as stories change until the feed ends at 10 p.m. ET. As with ''Morning Edition'', two hours of content are scheduled for each program. After 6 p.m. Eastern, the feed repeats the earlier hours for the Midwest and West Coast, although information is updated through the evening as appropriate.\n\n==Awards==\nMajor awards won by the show include the Ohio State Award, the [[Peabody Award]], the Overseas Press Club Award, the [[DuPont Awards|DuPont Award]], the American Women in Radio and Television Award, and the [[Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Award|Robert F. Kennedy Award]]. In 1993, the show was inducted into the [[National Radio Hall of Fame]], the first<ref>{{cite web |title=30th Anniversary Celebration of All Things Considered |url=https://www.npr.org/programs/atc/atc30/timeline/1993.html |website=[[National Public Radio]] |date=2001 |accessdate=2010-12-12}}</ref> public radio program to be given that honor.\n\nIn 2017, the first broadcast episode (from 1971) of ''All Things Considered'' was selected for preservation in the [[National Recording Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]].  Recordings in the collection are considered \"culturally, historically, or artistically significant.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-17-029/ | title=National Recording Registry Picks Are \"Over the Rainbow\" | work=Library of Congress | date=March 29, 2016 | accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcasts==\n[[ABC NewsRadio]] in [[Australia]] broadcasts a continuous hour of selected segments from each day's program between 12:00 and 13:00 [[Time in Australia|Australian Eastern Standard Time]] Monday to Friday. Segments A to D are edited together omitting local NPR news inserts.\n\n[[NPR Berlin]] in [[Germany]] aired in the local German timeslot, live from the U.S.\n\n==Hosts==\n===Weekday hosts===\n*[[Robert Conley (reporter)|Robert Conley]] (1971)\n*[[Mike Waters (radio host)|Mike Waters]] (1971\u20131974)\n*[[Susan Stamberg]] (1972\u20131986)\n*[[Bob Edwards]] (1974\u20131979)\n*[[Sanford J. Ungar|Sandy Ungar]] (1979\u20131982)\n*[[Noah Adams]] (1982\u20131987, 1989\u20132002)\n*[[Ren\u00e9e Montagne]] (1987\u20131989)\n*[[Robert Siegel]] (1987\u20132018)\n*[[Linda Wertheimer]] (1989\u20132002)\n*[[Michele Norris]] (2002\u20132011)\n*[[Melissa Block]] (2003\u20132015)\n*[[Kelly McEvers]] (2015\u20132018)\n*[[Audie Cornish]] (2012\u2013present)\n*[[Ari Shapiro]] (2015\u2013present)\n*[[Mary Louise Kelly]] (2018\u2013present)\n*[[Ailsa Chang]] (2018\u2013present)\n\n===Weekend hosts===\n*[[Robert Conley (reporter)|Robert Conley]] (1977)\n*[[Joe Frank]] (1978\u20131979)\n*[[Noah Adams]] (1979\u20131982)\n*[[Liane Hansen]] (1982\u20131984)\n*[[Lynn Neary]] (1984\u20131992)\n*[[Emil Guillermo]] (1989\u20131991)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aaldef.org/blog/archive/|title=Asian American Legal Defense and Education Fund|publisher=|accessdate=13 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017124925/http://aaldef.org/blog/archive/|archive-date=17 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Daniel Zwerdling]] (1993\u20131999)<ref>https://www.thirdcoastfestival.org/person/daniel-zwerdling</ref>\n*[[Lisa Simeone]] (2000\u20132002)\n*[[Steve Inskeep]] (2002\u20132004)\n*[[Deborah Elliott]] (2005\u20132007)\n*[[Andrea Seabrook]] (2007\u20132009)\n*[[Guy Raz]] (2009\u20132012)<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.npr.org/about/press/2012/113012.NPRExpandingTEDRadioHour.html |title=NPR Expanding 'TED Radio Hour' to Weekly Show, Hosted by Guy Raz |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=30 November 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Arun Rath]] (2013\u20132015)<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.npr.org/about/press/2013/071113.ArunRathWATCHost.html |title=NPR Names Arun Rath Host of 'Weekend All Things Considered{{'-}} |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=11 July 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Michel Martin]] (2015\u2013present)\n\n==Commentators==\n\n*[[Joe Bevilacqua]] (won 2006 [[New York Festivals]] award for ''All Things Considered: a tribute to [[Joe Barbera]]'')\n*[[David Budbill]] <!-- if ref is needed: https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/02/books/david-budbill-dead.html -->\n*[[Alan Cheuse]] (\u20132015)\n*[[Andrei Codrescu]]\n*[[Vertamae Grosvenor]]\n*[[Kevin Kling]]\n*[[John McIlwraith (commentator)|John McIlwraith]] (1990\u20132001)\n*[[Bob Mondello]]\n*[[Daniel Pinkwater]]\n*[[Reynolds Price]]\n*[[Ralph Schoenstein]]\n*[[Daniel Schorr]] (1985\u20132010)\n*[[Bailey White]]\n\n==Featured series==\nFrom time to time, NPR produces and distributes short series of radio pieces. Series that have aired during the show include:\n*''All Tech Considered''\n*''The Changing Face of America''\n*''In Character''\n*''Lost & Found Sound''\n*''The NPR 100''\n*''Prison Diaries''\n*''Teenage Diaries''\n*''[[This I Believe]]''\n*''Three Books''\n*''Three Minute Fiction''\n*''The Yiddish Radio Project''\n*''You Must Read This''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite journal |last=Magee |first=Sara |title=''All Things Considered'': A Content Analysis of National Public Radio's Flagship News Magazine from 1999\u20132009 |journal=Journal of Radio & Audio Media |date=2013 |volume=20 |issue=2 |pages=236\u2013250 |doi=10.1080/19376529.2013.823970}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.npr.org/programs/all-things-considered/}}\n\n{{NPR}}\n{{US Newsmagazine}}\n\n[[Category:1971 radio programme debuts]]\n[[Category:American news radio programs]]\n[[Category:NPR programs]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award-winning radio programs]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|News program on the American network National Public Radio (NPR)}}\n{{About|the NPR news program}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox Radio Show\n | show_name    = All Things Considered\n | image        = All things considered logo.svg\n | imagesize    = 144px\n | format       = [[News]]: analysis, commentary, features, interviews, specials\n | runtime      = 135 minutes weekdays;<br>50 minutes weekends approx.\n | presenter    = [[Audie Cornish]]<br/>[[Mary Louise Kelly]]<br/>[[Ari Shapiro]]<br/>[[Ailsa Chang]]\n | home_station = [[NPR]]\n | country      = United States\n | first_aired  = {{Start date|1971|05|03|}}\n | last_aired   = present\n | website      = {{URL|https://www.npr.org/programs/all-things-considered}}\n | podcast      = [https://www.npr.org/rss/rss.php?id=2 Podcast]\n}}\n'''''All Things Considered''''' ('''''ATC''''') is the flagship news program on the American network [[National Public Radio]] (NPR). It was the first news program on NPR, premiering on May 3, 1971. It is broadcast live on NPR affiliated stations in the [[United States]], and worldwide through several different outlets, formerly including the NPR [[Berlin, Germany|Berlin]] station in [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/worldwide |title=NPR Worldwide |website=[[National Public Radio]] |accessdate=2007-03-06}}</ref> ''All Things Considered'' and ''[[Morning Edition]]'' were the [[List of most-listened-to radio programs|highest rated public radio programs in the United States]] in 2002 and 2005.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news |first=Samuel G. |last= Freedman |title={{-'}}Listener Supported' and 'NPR': All Things Considered |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/17/books/review/17FREEDMA.html?scp=1&sq=%22all%20things%20considered%22&st=cse |department=Books |type=Book review |quote=National Public Radio alone reaches more than 20 million listeners, and its daily newsmagazine shows, ''All Things Considered'' and ''Morning Edition,'' attract a larger audience than any program except Rush Limbaugh's. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=17 July 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title=NPR Programs Attract Record-Breaking Audiences Public Radio Listenership at All-Time High |url=https://www.npr.org/about/press/020319.recordbreak.html |quote=Reflective of the intense news cycle following the September 11 terrorist attacks on the U.S., NPR's newsmagazines and talk programs increased audiences across the board. From Fall 2000 to Fall 2001, Morning Edition with Bob Edwards jumped from 10.7 to 13 million listeners; All Things Considered grew from 9.8 million to nearly 11.9 million; Talk of the Nation rocketed 40.8 percent to 3 million listeners; Fresh Air with Terry Gross grew 25.4 percent to nearly 4.2 million and The Diane Rehm Show grew 38.6 percent to nearly 1.4 million. Growth in the NPR news/talk audience outpaced similar gains realized by commercial news/talk radio.|work=[[National Public Radio]] |date=19 March 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081224022041/http://www.npr.org/about/press/020319.recordbreak.html |archivedate=2008-12-24 |url-status=live}}</ref> The show combines news, analysis, commentary, interviews, and special features, and its segments vary in length and style. ATC airs weekdays from 4:00&nbsp;p.m. to 6:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|Eastern Standard Time]] (live) or [[Pacific Standard Time (North America)|Pacific Standard Time]] (recorded with some updates; in Hawaii it airs as a fully recorded program) or from 3:00&nbsp;p.m. to 5:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Standard Time (North America)|Central Standard Time]]. A weekend version of ''ATC'', ''Weekend All Things Considered'', airs on Saturdays and Sundays.\n\n==Background==\n''ATC'' programming combines news, analysis, commentary, interviews, and special features broadcast live daily from 4:00&nbsp;p.m. to 6:00&nbsp;p.m. Eastern Time (3 to 5 pm Central Time) (20:00 to 22:00 [[UTC]]), and is re-fed with updates until 10 p.m. ET (9 p.m. CT) or 7 p.m. PT (02:00 UTC). Broadcasts run about 105 minutes with local content interspersed in between to complete two hours. In 2005, ''ATC'' aired on over 560 radio stations and reached an audience of approximately 12 million listeners each weekday, making it the third most listened to radio program in the United States after ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]'' and ''[[Morning Edition]]''.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> In September 2010, ''All Things Considered'' had an [[AQH Share|average quarter-hour audience]] of 1.8 million.<ref name=shepard>{{cite web |first=Alicia C. |last=Shepard |date=17 September 2010 |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/ombudsman/2010/09/15/129883401/harry-shearer-post |title=Harry Shearer and NPR: The Big Uneasy |department=NPR Ombudsman |website=[[NPR]]}}</ref> ''ATC'' is co-hosted by [[Audie Cornish]], [[Ari Shapiro]], and [[Mary Louise Kelly]], regularly by turns.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|last2=Pedersen|first2=Erik|title='All Things Considered': NPR Taps Mary Louise Kelly As Co-Host; Kelly McEvers Stepping Down|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/all-things-considered-npr-mary-louise-kelly-co-host-kelly-mcevers-robert-siegel-1202229086/|accessdate=8 January 2018|work=Deadline|date=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe first broadcast of ''ATC'' was fed to about 90 [[radio station]]s on May 3, 1971, with host [[Robert Conley (reporter)|Robert Conley]]. During the first week, these stations were not allowed to broadcast the feed \"live\" but could record it for later broadcast. The first story was about the march on [[Washington, D.C.]] and the growing anti-[[Vietnam War protests]] taking place there.<ref>{{cite web |title=30th Anniversary Celebration of All Things Considered |url=https://www.npr.org/programs/atc/atc30/timeline/1971.html |website=[[National Public Radio]] |date=2001}}</ref> NPR chose to place its inaugural daily newscast at the afternoon commute timeslot instead of the morning because many of its affiliates at that time did not sign on for the day until mid-morning or afterward.<ref>{{cite book |title=Conflicting Communication Interests in America: the case of National Public Radio |first=Tom |last=McCourt |location=Westport, Connecticut |publisher=Praeger |date=1999 |page=45 |isbn=}}</ref> It was not until 1979, by which time most affiliates had expanded their broadcast days to begin at 6 a.m. or earlier, that NPR premiered ''[[Morning Edition]]''.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\n'''''Weekend All Things Considered''''' (''WATC'') is a one-hour version of the show that premiered in 1977,<ref>{{cite web |title=About Weekend ATC |url=http://www.wlrh.org/Schedule/programdetail.asp?ProgramID=34 |website=[[WLRH]] public radio |date=2000 |accessdate=2010-12-12}}</ref> with host Robert Conley, and is broadcast on Saturdays and Sundays at 5 p.m. ET. Michel Martin now hosts the program. Former hosts also include [[Guy Raz]]. Raz left to be the host of the ''[[TED Radio Hour]]''. On February 13, 2013, NPR announced that it was relocating production of ''WATC'' to NPR West.<ref>{{cite press release |title=NPR Relocates 'Weekend All Things Considered' to NPR West |url=https://www.npr.org/about/press/2013/021313.WATCNPRWest.html |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=13 February 2013}}</ref> Production returned to Washington, DC in 2015.\n\n''ATC'' was excluded from the NPR deal with [[Sirius Satellite Radio]] so as not to compete with local stations airing the show.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lynette |last=Clemetson |title=All Things Considered, NPR's Growing Clout Alarms Member Stations |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/30/arts/all-things-considered-npr-s-growing-clout-alarms-member-stations.html |quote=NPR has a contract to program two Sirius channels, NPR Talk and NPR Now. But Mr. Klose said there were no plans to add the top-rated news programs to its satellite lineup against station wishes. ''We will respond to the will of the system,'' he said. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=30 August 2004}}</ref>\n\nTo coordinate the choice of interview partners in cultural coverage between ''ATC'' and other NPR shows (as of 2010: ''Morning Edition'', the weekend editions, ''[[Talk of the Nation]]'', and ''[[Tell Me More]]''), NPR set up a \"[[wikt:dibs|dibs]] list\" system around 2005, whereby the first show to declare interest in a particular guest can \"reserve\" that person.<ref name=shepard/>\n\nOn March 23, 2020, ''ATC'' launched '''''The National Conversation''''', a live [[call-in show]] addressing listener questions about the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]. The program airs from 9-10 p.m. ET on weeknights.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introducing 'The National Conversation With All Things Considered' |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/20/819186570/introducing-the-national-conversation-with-all-things-considered |website=NPR.org |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\nThe format is less rigid than that of ''Morning Edition'', with a wider array of type and length of stories. The length of stories tends to be greater than ''Morning Edition'', with some stories lasting for almost 23 minutes. Certain types of personal interest stories are almost always covered within this limit; those relating to hard news or entertainment tend to last the standard three-and-a-half to four minutes.\n\nThe program begins with the familiar [[Don Voegeli]] theme song<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/programs/asc/features/atc_theme/ |title=ATC Theme: The Story |website=[[All Songs Considered]] |accessdate=2013-08-10}}</ref> under a one-minute billboard of the stories to be covered during the hour. Then the standard five-minute NPR newscast is delivered from one minute to six minutes past the hour. The newscast offers a cutaway after three minutes (at four minutes past the hour), allowing stations to cover the last 2.5 minutes with evening rush-hour news and traffic reports. For those stations that run the newscast untouched, a 30-second music bed follows instead.\n\nThe first, or \"A\" segment, begins at :06:30 after the hour. It features important news stories, although not necessarily the most important news stories of the day. Often it is here that the most significant interviews or developing stories are placed. Segment A runs 11:29 in duration, and closes out at :18 after with a two-minute station break.\n\nAt :20:35 past the hour, ''ATC'' picks back up with Segment B. This segment, which runs 8:24, features more news and analysis, and often contains lighter stories and commentary. Segment B breaks for the half-hour at :29 past. The program goes into a one-minute local break.\n\nAt the bottom of the hour, ''ATC'' resumes with a \"host return\". In the 30-second return, the host or hosts discuss what's coming up in the remaining half-hour and intro the news. This is immediately followed by a 3:30 newscast which ends at :34 after the hour, followed by a one-minute local break.\n\nSegment C kicks off at :35:35 past the hour, and runs 8:24. Long feature stories are heard here, or as many as three shorter stories or commentaries may be heard as well. Segment D occurs immediately after Segment C at :44 past the hour, and runs for four minutes. Segment D is a designated cutaway for stations to run local commentary or features in lieu of the national segment. Segment D ends at :48 after the hour, and another two-minute break ensues. Occasionally, the show will \"break format\" and place a long, 12-minute story in Segments C and D without a local cutaway.\n\nSegment E starts at :50 after, and concludes the hour. The segment runs 8:09. Unlike ''Morning Edition'', there is no set format for this segment, although usually the second hour will contain an arts, culture, or lighter news story in this segment. Other times, hard news otherwise not fitting in the program may be placed here.\n\nStations receive a preliminary rundown before each broadcast (usually a few minutes before 4:00&nbsp;p.m. Eastern) denoting the timing and placement of stories so they can schedule local content as appropriate. This rundown is updated as stories change until the feed ends at 10 p.m. ET. As with ''Morning Edition'', two hours of content are scheduled for each program. After 6 p.m. Eastern, the feed repeats the earlier hours for the Midwest and West Coast, although information is updated through the evening as appropriate.\n\n==Awards==\nMajor awards won by the show include the Ohio State Award, the [[Peabody Award]], the Overseas Press Club Award, the [[DuPont Awards|DuPont Award]], the American Women in Radio and Television Award, and the [[Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Award|Robert F. Kennedy Award]]. In 1993, the show was inducted into the [[National Radio Hall of Fame]], the first<ref>{{cite web |title=30th Anniversary Celebration of All Things Considered |url=https://www.npr.org/programs/atc/atc30/timeline/1993.html |website=[[National Public Radio]] |date=2001 |accessdate=2010-12-12}}</ref> public radio program to be given that honor.\n\nIn 2017, the first broadcast episode (from 1971) of ''All Things Considered'' was selected for preservation in the [[National Recording Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]].  Recordings in the collection are considered \"culturally, historically, or artistically significant.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-17-029/ | title=National Recording Registry Picks Are \"Over the Rainbow\" | work=Library of Congress | date=March 29, 2016 | accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcasts==\n[[ABC NewsRadio]] in [[Australia]] broadcasts a continuous hour of selected segments from each day's program between 12:00 and 13:00 [[Time in Australia|Australian Eastern Standard Time]] Monday to Friday. Segments A to D are edited together omitting local NPR news inserts.\n\n[[NPR Berlin]] in [[Germany]] aired in the local German timeslot, live from the U.S.\n\n==Hosts==\n===Weekday hosts===\n*[[Robert Conley (reporter)|Robert Conley]] (1971)\n*[[Mike Waters (radio host)|Mike Waters]] (1971\u20131974)\n*[[Susan Stamberg]] (1972\u20131986)\n*[[Bob Edwards]] (1974\u20131979)\n*[[Sanford J. Ungar|Sandy Ungar]] (1979\u20131982)\n*[[Noah Adams]] (1982\u20131987, 1989\u20132002)\n*[[Ren\u00e9e Montagne]] (1987\u20131989)\n*[[Robert Siegel]] (1987\u20132018)\n*[[Linda Wertheimer]] (1989\u20132002)\n*[[Michele Norris]] (2002\u20132011)\n*[[Melissa Block]] (2003\u20132015)\n*[[Kelly McEvers]] (2015\u20132018)\n*[[Audie Cornish]] (2012\u2013present)\n*[[Ari Shapiro]] (2015\u2013present)\n*[[Mary Louise Kelly]] (2018\u2013present)\n*[[Ailsa Chang]] (2018\u2013present)\n\n===Weekend hosts===\n*[[Robert Conley (reporter)|Robert Conley]] (1977)\n*[[Joe Frank]] (1978\u20131979)\n*[[Noah Adams]] (1979\u20131982)\n*[[Liane Hansen]] (1982\u20131984)\n*[[Lynn Neary]] (1984\u20131992)\n*[[Emil Guillermo]] (1989\u20131991)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aaldef.org/blog/archive/|title=Asian American Legal Defense and Education Fund|publisher=|accessdate=13 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017124925/http://aaldef.org/blog/archive/|archive-date=17 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Daniel Zwerdling]] (1993\u20131999)<ref>[https://www.npr.org/people/4173096/daniel-zwerdling Daniel Zwerdling]. NPR. Retrieved on 2013-07-29.</ref>\n*[[Lisa Simeone]] (2000\u20132002)\n*[[Steve Inskeep]] (2002\u20132004)\n*[[Deborah Elliott]] (2005\u20132007)\n*[[Andrea Seabrook]] (2007\u20132009)\n*[[Guy Raz]] (2009\u20132012)<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.npr.org/about/press/2012/113012.NPRExpandingTEDRadioHour.html |title=NPR Expanding 'TED Radio Hour' to Weekly Show, Hosted by Guy Raz |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=30 November 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Arun Rath]] (2013\u20132015)<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.npr.org/about/press/2013/071113.ArunRathWATCHost.html |title=NPR Names Arun Rath Host of 'Weekend All Things Considered{{'-}} |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=11 July 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Michel Martin]] (2015\u2013present)\n\n==Commentators==\n\n*[[Joe Bevilacqua]] (won 2006 [[New York Festivals]] award for ''All Things Considered: a tribute to [[Joe Barbera]]'')\n*[[David Budbill]] <!-- if ref is needed: https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/02/books/david-budbill-dead.html -->\n*[[Alan Cheuse]] (\u20132015)\n*[[Andrei Codrescu]]\n*[[Vertamae Grosvenor]]\n*[[Kevin Kling]]\n*[[John McIlwraith (commentator)|John McIlwraith]] (1990\u20132001)\n*[[Bob Mondello]]\n*[[Daniel Pinkwater]]\n*[[Reynolds Price]]\n*[[Ralph Schoenstein]]\n*[[Daniel Schorr]] (1985\u20132010)\n*[[Bailey White]]\n\n==Featured series==\nFrom time to time, NPR produces and distributes short series of radio pieces. Series that have aired during the show include:\n*''All Tech Considered''\n*''The Changing Face of America''\n*''In Character''\n*''Lost & Found Sound''\n*''The NPR 100''\n*''Prison Diaries''\n*''Teenage Diaries''\n*''[[This I Believe]]''\n*''Three Books''\n*''Three Minute Fiction''\n*''The Yiddish Radio Project''\n*''You Must Read This''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite journal |last=Magee |first=Sara |title=''All Things Considered'': A Content Analysis of National Public Radio's Flagship News Magazine from 1999\u20132009 |journal=Journal of Radio & Audio Media |date=2013 |volume=20 |issue=2 |pages=236\u2013250 |doi=10.1080/19376529.2013.823970}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.npr.org/programs/all-things-considered/}}\n\n{{NPR}}\n{{US Newsmagazine}}\n\n[[Category:1971 radio programme debuts]]\n[[Category:American news radio programs]]\n[[Category:NPR programs]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award-winning radio programs]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n", "name_user": "Ben76266", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeekend hosts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All_Things_Considered"}
{"title_page": "British Rail Class 717", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox train\n| background = \n| name = British Rail Class 717\n| image = 717009 OKL.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = A [[Govia Thameslink Railway|Great Northern]] Class 717 at [[Oakleigh Park railway station|Oakleigh Park]]\n| interiorimage = File:GTR_Class_717_Interior.jpg\n| interiorimagealt = \n| interiorcaption = The interior of a Class 717\n| service = 28 September 2018 \u2013 present\n| manufacturer = [[Siemens Mobility]]\n| factory = [[Krefeld, Germany]]\n| family = [[Siemens Desiro|''Desiro City'']]\n| replaced = {{brc|313}}\n| yearconstruction = 2018\u20132019\n| refurbishment = \n| yearscrapped = \n| numberbuilt = 25\n| operator = [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]]\n| depots = Hornsey EMUD\n| lines = [[Northern City Line]]\n| carbody = \n| trainlength = {{convert|121674|mm|ftin|frac=8|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"siemens_leaflet\">{{cite press release |title=Desiro City Class 717 Electrical Multiple Units for Govia Thameslink Railway |url=https://assets.new.siemens.com/siemens/assets/public.1536773109.f3fefc372beb2112fe20b2704888468d2157dc27.db-desiro-city-moorgate-en.pdf|publisher=Siemens Mobility GmbH |location=Munich |type=Leaflet |id=Article No. MOML-T10055-00-7600}}</ref>\n| carlength = {{convert|20.2|m|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|2.80|m|abbr=on}}\n| height = \n| floorheight = \n| platformheight = \n| entrylevelorstep = \n| doors = \n| art-sections = \n| wheeldiameter = \n| wheelbase = \n| maxspeed = {{convert|85|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Cab. 717003. Wildenrath. Germany. 2.5.18|url=http://PaulBigland.zenfolio.com/p292832614/eaa06118c|website=paulbigland.zenfolio.com|publisher=Paul Bigland|accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|204|t|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"siemens_leaflet\" />\n| axleload = \n| traction = \n| engine = \n| poweroutput = {{convert|1200|kW|abbr=on}} (at wheel)<ref name=\"siemens_leaflet\" />\n| tractiveeffort = \n| transmission = \n| acceleration = {{convert|0.85|m/s2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"siemens_leaflet\" />\n| deceleration = \n| aux = \n| powersupply = \n| hvac = \n| electricsystem = {{25 kV 50 Hz}} [[Overhead line|Catenary]]<br> 750&nbsp;[[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[Third rail]]\n| collectionmethod = [[Pantograph (transport)|Pantograph]] (AC)<br>[[Contact shoe]] (DC)\n| uicclass = Bo'Bo'+2'2'+2'2'+Bo'Bo'+2'2'+<br />Bo'Bo'<ref name=\"siemens_leaflet\" />\n| aarwheels = \n| bogies = \n| brakes = \n| safety = [[European Train Control System|ETCS]] (B3MR1), [[Automatic Warning System|AWS]], [[Train Protection & Warning System|TPWS]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Siemens Desiro City Moorgate (Class 717): Derogation for a Project at an Advanced Stage of Development |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/siemens-desiro-city-moorgate-class-717-trains-decision |publisher=Department for Transport |accessdate=3 October 2018 |location=London |format=letter |date=12 January 2018}}</ref> [[Tripcock]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Side view of leading bogie. 717012. Wildenrath. Germany. 2.5.18|url=https://paulbigland.zenfolio.com/p292832614/hAA06118C#ha9fbf05e|website=paulbigland.zenfolio.com|publisher=Paul Bigland|accessdate=3 October 2018}}</ref>\n| coupling = \n| multipleworking = \n| gauge = {{Track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| notes = Sources : [[#dat1|Desiro City (Class 700) data sheet]]<br>Except where noted\n}}\nThe '''British Rail Class 717'''<ref name=rail_jun_16>{{cite web|title=New Govia Thameslink Railway trains to be Class 717s|url=http://www.railmagazine.com/news/fleet/2016/06/08/new-govia-thameslink-railway-trains-to-be-class-717s|website=RAIL magazine|publisher=RAIL magazine|accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref> is an [[electric multiple unit]] used by [[Govia Thameslink Railway]], on its [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]]  Hertford Loop and Welwyn stopping routes. They are manufactured by German rolling stock manufacturer [[Siemens Mobility|Siemens]], mainly for services from [[Moorgate railway station|Moorgate]] station, in London. A total of 25 six-car units are to be built. Starting in January 2019, limited preview services began<ref name=railserviceentry/> and the phase-in of regular service began in March 2019.<ref name=fullserviceentry>{{cite web |url=https://www.railmagazine.com/news/network/great-northern-class-717s-finally-enter-passenger-service |title=Great Northern Class 717s finally enter passenger service}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greatnorthernrail.com/717trains|title=New Trains for Moorgate services|publisher=Great Northern|accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nUpon winning the [[Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern franchise]], [[Govia Thameslink Railway]] (GTR) announced that it would seek to replace the existing {{BRC|313}} units (which were 40 years old in 2016) operating on services to and from Moorgate, with up to 25 six-car units intended to be procured.<ref>{{cite web|title=Thameslink Franchise operator announced|url=http://www.rail.co.uk/rail-news/2014/thameslink-franchise-operator-announced/|website=rail.co.uk|publisher=rail.co.uk|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> In December 2015, GTR announced that it had selected Siemens to provide this new fleet as a follow-on order from the main [[British Rail Class 700|Class 700]] order, with entry into service expected from March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Siemens selected to supply Moorgate suburban EMU fleet|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/traction-rolling-stock/single-view/view/siemens-selected-to-supply-moorgate-suburban-emu-fleet.html|website=Railway Gazette|publisher=Railway Gazette|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref>\nThe order was finalised in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=GTR strikes \u00a3200m-plus deal for new train fleet serving City of London|url=https://www.siemens.co.uk/en/news_press/index/news_archive/2016/gtr-strikes-200m-plus-deal-for-new-train-fleet-serving-city-of-london.htm|website=Siemens UK|publisher=Siemens UK|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.markprisk.com/sites/www.markprisk.com/files/2017-12/GTR%20response%20to%20meeting%20with%20Mark%20Prisk%20MP.pdf |title=:Letter from GTR to MP Mark Prisk}}</ref>\n\nA significant difference between Class 717s and the earlier Class 700s is the provision of fold-down emergency doors at both ends of each train. These are required for emergency evacuation of passengers<ref name=\"rail_jun_16\"/> while inside the [[Northern City Line|Moorgate tunnels]].<ref name=\"SexAp\">{{cite book |author=Network Rail |authorlink=Network Rail |title=London North Eastern Route Sectional Appendix LOR 105 Seq 001|volume=Module LNE1 |date=2017-06-03 |id=NR30018/02 |page=41}}</ref>\n\nSiemens began testing the Class 717 units in Germany during June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.railwaymagazine.co.uk/testing-begins-on-gtrs-new-class-717s-in-germany/ |title=Testing begins on GTR\u2019s new Class 717s in Germany}}</ref> The first unit operated a single preview service in late September 2018, with gradual introduction from the spring of 2019.<ref name=railserviceentry>{{cite web|url=https://www.railmagazine.com/news/network/new-great-northern-class-717-carries-first-passengers |title=New Great Northern Class 717 carries first passengers}}</ref>\n\n==Fleet details==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Class\n!Operator\n!No. Built\n!Year Built\n!Cars per unit\n!Unit nos.\n|-\n|'''Class 717'''\n|[[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]]\n|align=center|25\n|align=center|2018-2019\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|717001&ndash;717025\n|-\n|}\n[[File:Great Northern Class 717.png|none|thumb|785x785px|Great Northern Class 717]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[British Rail Class 707]] - A unit based on the ''Desiro City'' platform constructed for [[South West Trains]].\n* [[British Rail Class 700]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite press release |url=http://www.siemens.co.uk/pool/news_press/news_archive/2013/desiro-city-datasheet-high-res.pdf |title=Desiro City \u2013 Electrical Multiple Unit for Thameslink |type=Datasheet |publisher=[[Siemens]] |year=2013 |accessdate=7 June 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6L4c3OQs8?url=http://www.siemens.co.uk/pool/news_press/news_archive/2013/desiro-city-datasheet-high-res.pdf |archivedate=12 November 2013 |ref=dat1 |df=dmy }}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.greatnorthernrail.com/about-us/our-commitments/improving-your-railway/new-trains-for-moorgate-services Great Northern Rail] page about the introduction of the 717s\n{{commonscat}}\n\n{{UK Desiro|state=collapsed}}\n{{British Rail EMU|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:British Rail electric multiple units|717]]\n[[Category:Siemens multiple units]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 2018]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox train\n| background = \n| name = British Rail Class 717\n| image = 717009 OKL.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = A [[Govia Thameslink Railway|Great Northern]] Class 717 at [[Oakleigh Park railway station|Oakleigh Park]]\n| interiorimage = File:GTR_Class_717_Interior.jpg\n| interiorimagealt = \n| interiorcaption = The interior of a Class 717\n| service = 28 September 2018 \u2013 present\n| manufacturer = [[Siemens Mobility]]\n| factory = [[Krefeld, Germany]]\n| family = [[Siemens Desiro|''Desiro City'']]\n| replaced = {{brc|313}}\n| yearconstruction = 2018\u20132019\n| refurbishment = \n| yearscrapped = \n| numberbuilt = 25\n| operator = [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]]\n| depots = Hornsey EMUD\n| lines = [[Northern City Line]]\n| carbody = \n| trainlength = {{convert|121674|mm|ftin|frac=8|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"siemens_leaflet\">{{cite press release |title=Desiro City Class 717 Electrical Multiple Units for Govia Thameslink Railway |url=https://assets.new.siemens.com/siemens/assets/public.1536773109.f3fefc372