{"title_page": "Teapot Dome scandal", "text_new": "{{redirect|Teapot Dome}}\n{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|1921\u20131923 U.S. Cabinet bribery scandal}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2019}}\n[[File:Edward Doheny Testifying 2 crop.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Oil businessman [[Edward L. Doheny]] (at table, second from right) testifying before the Senate committee investigating the Teapot Dome oil leases, 1924]]\n\nThe '''Teapot Dome scandal''' was a [[bribery]] scandal involving the administration of United States President [[Warren G. Harding]] from 1921 to 1923. [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Albert Bacon Fall]] had leased [[United States Navy|Navy]] [[petroleum]] reserves at [[Teapot Rock|Teapot Dome]] in [[Wyoming]], and two locations in [[California]], to private oil companies at low rates without competitive bidding. The leases were the subject of a seminal investigation by Senator [[Thomas J. Walsh]]. Convicted of accepting bribes from the oil companies, Fall became the first [[Cabinet of the United States|presidential cabinet]] member to go to prison; no one was convicted of paying the bribes.\n\nBefore the [[Watergate scandal]], Teapot Dome was regarded as the \"greatest and most sensational [[List of federal political scandals in the United States|scandal in the history of American politics]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gilderlehrman.org/historynow/historian5.php |title=Graft and Oil: How Teapot Dome Became the Greatest Political Scandal of its Time |last=Cherny |first=Robert W |work=History Now |publisher=[[Gilder Lehrman Institute of American History]] |accessdate=May 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709015531/http://www.gilderlehrman.org/historynow/historian5.php |archivedate=July 9, 2010 }}</ref> It damaged the reputation of the Harding administration, which was already severely diminished by its controversial handling of the [[Great Railroad Strike of 1922]] and Harding's veto of the [[World War Adjusted Compensation Act|Bonus Bill]] in 1922.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.presidentprofiles.com/Grant-Eisenhower/Warren-G-Harding-Domestic-and-foreign-affairs.html | title = Grant-Eisenhower | contribution = Warren G Harding: Domestic & foreign affairs | publisher = President profiles}}.</ref> Congress subsequently passed legislation, enduring to this day, giving subpoena power to the House and Senate for review of tax records of any US citizen without regard to elected or appointed position, nor subject to White House interference.<ref name=Paletta9April>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-treasury-lawyers-discussed-trumps-tax-returns-before-democrats-request-mnuchin-says/2019/04/09/9693618e-5ad2-11e9-842d-7d3ed7eb3957_story.html |title=Mnuchin reveals White House lawyers consulted Treasury on Trump tax returns, despite law meant to limit political involvement |work=The Washington Post|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|first=Damian|last=Paletta}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Teapot Rock postcard crop.jpg|thumb|Teapot Dome around the time of the scandal, featuring Teapot Rock (from postcard c. 1922)]]\n\nIn the early 20th century, the U.S. Navy largely converted from [[coal]] to [[fuel oil]]. To ensure that the Navy would always have enough fuel available, several oil-producing areas were designated as naval oil reserves by [[William Howard Taft|President Taft]]. In 1921, President Harding issued an [[executive order]] that transferred control of [[Teapot Rock|Teapot Dome Oil Field]] in [[Natrona County, Wyoming]], and the [[Elk Hills Oil Field|Elk Hills]] and [[Buena Vista Oil Field]]s in [[Kern County, California]], from the [[United States Department of the Navy|Navy Department]] to the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of the Interior]]. This was not implemented until 1922, when Interior Secretary Fall persuaded [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Edwin Denby (politician)|Edwin C. Denby]] to transfer control.\n\nLater in 1922, Interior Secretary Albert Fall leased the oil production rights at Teapot Dome to [[Harry Ford Sinclair|Harry F. Sinclair]] of Mammoth Oil, a subsidiary of [[Sinclair Oil Corporation]]. He also leased the Elk Hills reserve to [[Edward L. Doheny]] of [[Pan American Petroleum and Transport Company]]. Both leases were issued without competitive bidding. This manner of leasing was legal under the [[Mineral Leasing Act of 1920]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.blm.gov/pgdata/etc/medialib/blm/ut/vernal_fo/lands___minerals.Par.6287.File.dat/MineralLeasingAct1920.pdf | title= Mineral Leasing Act of 1920 as Amended (re-transcribed 2007-08-07) | publisher= Bureau of Land Management, U.S. Department of the Interior | accessdate=2014-09-08 }}</ref>\n\nThe lease terms were very favorable to the oil companies, which secretly made Fall a rich man. Fall had received a no-interest loan from Doheny of $100,000, <ref>{{cite web |date=November 23, 1926 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/11/25/archives/fall-and-doheny-fight-to-bar-senate-records-on-100000-cash-loan.html |title=FALL AND DOHENY FIGHT TO BAR SENATE RECORDS ON $100,000 CASH LOAN; VITAL POINT IS RAISED : Defense Halts Move to Bare Admissions Made by Doheny. COURT AWAITS ARGUMENT McLean Testifies That Fall Asked Him to Subscribe to a Falsehood on Loan. LENROOT RELATES EVASIONS Senator Says the Ex-Secretary Finally Asserted Publisher Was Source of Funds. Witnesses Tell of Efforts by Fall to Hide Source of $100,000 Loan |publisher=New York Times}}</ref> or (about ${{Format price|{{inflation|US|100000|1921}}}} today{{inflation-fn |US}}) in November 1921. He received other gifts from Doheny and Sinclair totaling about $404,000 (about ${{Format price|{{inflation|US|404000|1921}}}} today{{inflation-fn|US}}). This money changing hands was illegal, not the leases. Fall attempted to keep his actions secret, but the sudden improvement in his standard of living was suspect.\n\n==Investigation and outcome==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2017}}\nIn April 1922, a Wyoming oil operator wrote to his Senator, [[John B. Kendrick]], angered that Sinclair had been given a contract to the lands in a secret deal. Kendrick did not respond, but two days later on April 15, he introduced a resolution calling for an investigation of the deal.<ref>{{cite book | author = Davis, Margaret L | title= Dark Side of Fortune: Triumph and Scandal in the Life of Oil Tycoon Edward L. Doheny| publisher =[[University of California Press]]|year=2001|isbn=9780520927056|page=149|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=q65CsgOv7dMC&pg=PA149}}</ref> [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Senator [[Robert M. La Follette Sr.]] of [[Wisconsin]] led an investigation by the Senate Committee on Public Lands. At first, La Follette believed Fall was innocent. However, his suspicions were aroused after his own office in the [[Senate Office Building]] was ransacked.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/minute/Senate_Investigates_the_Teapot_Dome_Scandal.htm|title=Senate Investigates the \"Teapot Dome\" Scandal |work= Historical Minutes: 1921\u20131940|publisher=Art & History, United States Senate}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| via=Google Books |title=The Ohio Presidents: Eight Men and a Binding Political Philosophy in the White House, 1841-1923 |\nauthor=Quentin R. Skrabec, Jr. |\npublisher=McFarland |year= 2018\n|ISBN=1476669309 |page= 199 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=T7VqDwAAQBAJ}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Albert B. Fall with map background.jpg|thumb|[[Albert B. Fall]] was the first U.S. cabinet official sentenced to prison.]]\n\nDemocrat [[Thomas J. Walsh]] of [[Montana]], the most junior minority member, led a lengthy inquiry.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=US Senate |title=Thomas J. Walsh: A Featured Biography |url=https://www.senate.gov/senators/FeaturedBios/Featured_Bio_Walsh.htm}}</ref> For two years, Walsh pushed forward while Fall stepped backward, covering his tracks as he went. No evidence of wrongdoing was initially uncovered, as the leases were legal enough, but records kept disappearing mysteriously. Fall had made the leases appear legitimate, but his acceptance of the money was his undoing. By 1924, the remaining unanswered question was how Fall had become so rich so quickly and easily.\n\nMoney from the bribes had gone to Fall's cattle ranch and investments in his business. Finally, as the investigation was winding down with Fall apparently innocent, Walsh uncovered a piece of evidence Fall had failed to cover up: Doheny's $100,000 loan to Fall. This discovery broke open the scandal. Civil and criminal suits related to the scandal continued throughout the 1920s. In 1927, the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] ruled that the oil leases had been corruptly obtained. The Court invalidated the Elk Hills lease in February 1927, and the Teapot Dome lease in October. Both reserves were returned to the Navy.<ref name=revenues/>\n\nIn 1929, Fall was found guilty of accepting bribes from Doheny.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cabinet member found guilty in Teapot Dome scandal\n|url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/cabinet-member-guilty-in-teapot-dome-scandal |work=On ThisDay In History |publisher=History.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |agency=UPI |title=On This Day: Interior Secretary Fall found guilty in Teapot Dome scandal  |date=October 25, 2019 |url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/10/25/On-This-Day-Interior-Secretary-Fall-found-guilty-in-Teapot-Dome-scandal/4141571969653/}}</ref> Conversely, in 1930, Doheny was acquitted of paying bribes to Fall.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1977/06/09/uncovering-a-coverup-on-teapot-dome/93c16e16-8e32-4bf0-aabd-bb83c9bebd0d/ |title=Uncovering a Coverup on Teapot Dome |author= Chalmers M. Roberts|date= June 9, 1977}}</ref> Further, Doheny's corporation foreclosed on Fall's home<ref>{{cite book |via=Google books |title=Cold Case: The Assassination of Pat Garrett: Investigating History's Mysteries |author=W. C. Jameson | publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2020 |ISBN = 149304589X | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Vi_XDwAAQBAJ |page=204}}</ref> in the [[Tularosa Basin]], New Mexico, because of \"unpaid loans\" that turned out to be that same $100,000 bribe. Sinclair served six months in jail on a charge of [[jury tampering]].<ref>{{cite book |last=McCartney |first=Laton |title=The Teapot Dome Scandal: How Big Oil Bought the Harding White House and Tried to Steal the Country |location=New York |publisher=[[Random House]] |year=2008 |isbn=978-1-4000-6316-1 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/teapotdomescanda00mcca }}</ref>\n\nAlthough Fall was to blame for this scandal, Harding's reputation was sullied because of his involvement with the wrong people. Evidence proving Fall's guilt only arose after Harding's death in 1923.<ref>{{cite book|last1=MacDonald|first1=Scott B.|last2=Hughes|first2=Jane E.|title=Separating Fools from Their Money: A History of American Financial Scandals|orig-year=1st pub. 2007|publisher=Transaction|location=New Brunswick, N.J.|isbn=978-0-7658-0356-6|date=2015|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/separat_mac_2007_00_2620}}</ref>\n\nAnother significant outcome was the Supreme Court's ruling in ''[[McGrain v. Daugherty]]'' (1927) which, for the first time, explicitly established that [[Congress of the United States|Congress]] had the power to compel testimony.<ref name=\"oyez\">{{Cite web | title = McGrain v. Daugherty | publisher = Oyez.org | url = https://www.oyez.org/cases/1901-1939/1924/1924_28 | accessdate = 2 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe oil field was then idled for 49 years, but went back into production in 1976. After earning over $569 million in revenue having extracted {{convert|22|e6oilbbl|lk=in}} of oil over the previous 39 years, in February 2015, the [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] sold the oil field for $45 million to New York-based Stranded Oil Resources Corp.<ref name=revenues>[http://www.denverpost.com/2015/01/30/government-sells-scandalized-teapot-dome-oilfield-for-45-million Government sells scandalized Teapot Dome oilfield for $45 million], ''[[Denver Post]]'', [[Associated Press]]'', January 30, 2015. Retrieved 4 June 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Alleghany Capital Corporation Announces Acquisition Of \"Teapot Dome Oilfield\" By Stranded Oil Resources Corporation |date= January 30, 2015 |author=Alleghany Capital |agency=PR Newswire |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/alleghany-capital-corporation-announces-acquisition-of-teapot-dome-oilfield-by-stranded-oil-resources-corporation-300028515.html}}</ref>\n\n==Comparison==\n\nThe Teapot Dome scandal has historically been regarded as the worst such scandal in the United States \u2013 the \"[[high water mark]]\" of cabinet corruption. It is often used as a benchmark for comparison with subsequent scandals. In particular it has been compared to the [[Watergate scandal]], in which a cabinet member, Attorney General [[John N. Mitchell]], went to prison, the second time in American history that a member of cabinet has been incarcerated.<ref>{{cite book|title=Watergate & the Teapot Dome Scandal: The History and Legacy of America's Most Notorious Government Scandals|date=November 2, 2016|publisher=Charles River Editors |edition=Kindle |asin=B01N9IMB2P}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Uncovering a Coverup on Teapot Dome|last=Roberts|first=Chalmers M.|date=June 9, 1977|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Little Green House on K Street]]\n* [[List of federal political scandals in the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* Bates, J. Leonard. ''The Origins of Teapot Dome''. Urbana, IL: University of Illinois Press, 1963.\n* Bennett, Leslie E. [http://academic.brooklyn.cuny.edu/history/johnson/teapotdome.htm \"One Lesson From History: Appointment of Special Counsel and the Investigation of the Teapot Dome Scandal\"]. Washington, D.C.: Brookings Institution, 1999.\n* Ise, John. ''The United States Oil Policy''. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press, 1926.\n* Murphy, Blakely M. (ed.) ''Conservation of Oil and Gas: A Legal History''. Chicago: Section of Mineral Law, American Bar Association, 1949.\n* [[Burl Noggle|Noggle, Burl]]. ''Teapot Dome: Oil and Politics in the 1920s''. Baton Rouge, LA: Louisiana State University Press, 1962.\n* Werner, M. R. and Starr, John. ''Teapot Dome''. New York: Viking Press, 1959.\n\n{{US federal public corruption law}}\n{{US history}}\n{{Special Prosecutors and Independent Counsels of the U.S.}}\n\n{{coord|43.2885808|N|106.1733516|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Teapot Dome scandal| ]]\n[[Category:Petroleum in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political corruption scandals in the United States]]\n[[Category:1920s in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bribery scandals]]\n[[Category:Cover-ups]]\n[[Category:History of Kern County, California]]\n[[Category:History of the San Joaquin Valley]]\n[[Category:History of Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Natrona County, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Oil fields in Kern County, California]]\n[[Category:Petroleum in California]]\n[[Category:Sinclair Oil Corporation]]\n[[Category:1922 in California]]\n[[Category:1923 in California]]\n[[Category:1922 in Wyoming]]\n[[Category:1923 in Wyoming]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Teapot Dome}}\n{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|1921\u20131923 U.S. Cabinet bribery scandal}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2019}}\n[[File:Edward Doheny Testifying 2 crop.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Oil businessman [[Edward L. Doheny]] (at table, second from right) testifying before the Senate committee investigating the Teapot Dome oil leases, 1924]]\n\nThe '''Teapot Dome scandal''' was a [[bribery]] scandal involving the administration of United States President [[Warren G. Harding]] from 1921 to 1923. [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Albert Bacon Fall]] had leased [[United States Navy|Navy]] [[petroleum]] reserves at [[Teapot Rock|Teapot Dome]] in [[Wyoming]], and two locations in [[California]], to private oil companies at low rates without competitive bidding. The leases were the subject of a seminal investigation by Senator [[Thomas J. Walsh]]. Convicted of accepting bribes from the oil companies, Fall became the first [[Cabinet of the United States|presidential cabinet]] member to go to prison; no one was convicted of paying the bribes.\n\nBefore the [[Watergate scandal]], Teapot Dome was regarded as the \"greatest and most sensational [[List of federal political scandals in the United States|scandal in the history of American politics]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gilderlehrman.org/historynow/historian5.php |title=Graft and Oil: How Teapot Dome Became the Greatest Political Scandal of its Time |last=Cherny |first=Robert W |work=History Now |publisher=[[Gilder Lehrman Institute of American History]] |accessdate=May 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709015531/http://www.gilderlehrman.org/historynow/historian5.php |archivedate=July 9, 2010 }}</ref> It damaged the reputation of the Harding administration, which was already severely diminished by its controversial handling of the [[Great Railroad Strike of 1922]] and Harding's veto of the [[World War Adjusted Compensation Act|Bonus Bill]] in 1922.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.presidentprofiles.com/Grant-Eisenhower/Warren-G-Harding-Domestic-and-foreign-affairs.html | title = Grant-Eisenhower | contribution = Warren G Harding: Domestic & foreign affairs | publisher = President profiles}}.</ref> Congress subsequently passed legislation, enduring to this day, giving subpoena power to the House and Senate for review of tax records of any US citizen without regard to elected or appointed position, nor subject to White House interference.<ref name=Paletta9April>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-treasury-lawyers-discussed-trumps-tax-returns-before-democrats-request-mnuchin-says/2019/04/09/9693618e-5ad2-11e9-842d-7d3ed7eb3957_story.html |title=Mnuchin reveals White House lawyers consulted Treasury on Trump tax returns, despite law meant to limit political involvement |work=The Washington Post|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|first=Damian|last=Paletta}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Teapot Rock postcard crop.jpg|thumb|Teapot Dome around the time of the scandal, featuring Teapot Rock (from postcard c. 1922)]]\n\nIn the early 20th century, the U.S. Navy largely converted from [[coal]] to [[fuel oil]]. To ensure that the Navy would always have enough fuel available, several oil-producing areas were designated as naval oil reserves by [[William Howard Taft|President Taft]]. In 1921, President Harding issued an [[executive order]] that transferred control of [[Teapot Rock|Teapot Dome Oil Field]] in [[Natrona County, Wyoming]], and the [[Elk Hills Oil Field|Elk Hills]] and [[Buena Vista Oil Field]]s in [[Kern County, California]], from the [[United States Department of the Navy|Navy Department]] to the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of the Interior]]. This was not implemented until 1922, when Interior Secretary Fall persuaded [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Edwin Denby (politician)|Edwin C. Denby]] to transfer control.\n\nLater in 1922, Interior Secretary Albert Fall leased the oil production rights at Teapot Dome to [[Harry Ford Sinclair|Harry F. Sinclair]] of Mammoth Oil, a subsidiary of [[Sinclair Oil Corporation]]. He also leased the Elk Hills reserve to [[Edward L. Doheny]] of [[Pan American Petroleum and Transport Company]]. Both leases were issued without competitive bidding. This manner of leasing was legal under the [[Mineral Leasing Act of 1920]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.blm.gov/pgdata/etc/medialib/blm/ut/vernal_fo/lands___minerals.Par.6287.File.dat/MineralLeasingAct1920.pdf | title= Mineral Leasing Act of 1920 as Amended (re-transcribed 2007-08-07) | publisher= Bureau of Land Management, U.S. Department of the Interior | accessdate=2014-09-08 }}</ref>\n\nThe lease terms were very favorable to the oil companies, which secretly made Fall a rich man. Fall had received a no-interest loan from Doheny of $100,000, <ref>{{cite web |date=November 23, 1926 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/11/25/archives/fall-and-doheny-fight-to-bar-senate-records-on-100000-cash-loan.html |title=FALL AND DOHENY FIGHT TO BAR SENATE RECORDS ON $100,000 CASH LOAN; VITAL POINT IS RAISED : Defense Halts Move to Bare Admissions Made by Doheny. COURT AWAITS ARGUMENT McLean Testifies That Fall Asked Him to Subscribe to a Falsehood on Loan. LENROOT RELATES EVASIONS Senator Says the Ex-Secretary Finally Asserted Publisher Was Source of Funds. Witnesses Tell of Efforts by Fall to Hide Source of $100,000 Loan |publisher=New York Times}}</ref> or (about ${{Format price|{{inflation|US|100000|1921}}}} today{{inflation-fn |US}}) in November 1921. He received other gifts from Doheny and Sinclair totaling about $404,000 (about ${{Format price|{{inflation|US|404000|1921}}}} today{{inflation-fn|US}}). This money changing hands was illegal, not the leases. Fall attempted to keep his actions secret, but the sudden improvement in his standard of living was suspect.\n\n==Investigation and outcome==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2017}}\nIn April 1922, a Wyoming oil operator wrote to his Senator, [[John B. Kendrick]], angered that Sinclair had been given a contract to the lands in a secret deal. Kendrick did not respond, but two days later on April 15, he introduced a resolution calling for an investigation of the deal.<ref>{{cite book | author = Davis, Margaret L | title= Dark Side of Fortune: Triumph and Scandal in the Life of Oil Tycoon Edward L. Doheny| publisher =[[University of California Press]]|year=2001|isbn=9780520927056|page=149|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=q65CsgOv7dMC&pg=PA149}}</ref> [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Senator [[Robert M. La Follette Sr.]] of [[Wisconsin]] led an investigation by the Senate Committee on Public Lands. At first, La Follette believed Fall was innocent. However, his suspicions were aroused after his own office in the [[Senate Office Building]] was ransacked.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/minute/Senate_Investigates_the_Teapot_Dome_Scandal.htm|title=Senate Investigates the \"Teapot Dome\" Scandal |work= Historical Minutes: 1921\u20131940|publisher=Art & History, United States Senate}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| via=Google Books |title=The Ohio Presidents: Eight Men and a Binding Political Philosophy in the White House, 1841-1923 |\nauthor=Quentin R. Skrabec, Jr. |\npublisher=McFarland |year= 2018\n|ISBN=1476669309 |page= 199 |url=ttps://books.google.ca/books?id=T7VqDwAAQBAJ}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Albert B. Fall with map background.jpg|thumb|[[Albert B. Fall]] was the first U.S. cabinet official sentenced to prison.]]\n\nDemocrat [[Thomas J. Walsh]] of [[Montana]], the most junior minority member, led a lengthy inquiry.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=US Senate |title=Thomas J. Walsh: A Featured Biography |url=https://www.senate.gov/senators/FeaturedBios/Featured_Bio_Walsh.htm}}</ref> For two years, Walsh pushed forward while Fall stepped backward, covering his tracks as he went. No evidence of wrongdoing was initially uncovered, as the leases were legal enough, but records kept disappearing mysteriously. Fall had made the leases appear legitimate, but his acceptance of the money was his undoing. By 1924, the remaining unanswered question was how Fall had become so rich so quickly and easily.\n\nMoney from the bribes had gone to Fall's cattle ranch and investments in his business. Finally, as the investigation was winding down with Fall apparently innocent, Walsh uncovered a piece of evidence Fall had failed to cover up: Doheny's $100,000 loan to Fall. This discovery broke open the scandal. Civil and criminal suits related to the scandal continued throughout the 1920s. In 1927, the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] ruled that the oil leases had been corruptly obtained. The Court invalidated the Elk Hills lease in February 1927, and the Teapot Dome lease in October. Both reserves were returned to the Navy.<ref name=revenues/>\n\nIn 1929, Fall was found guilty of accepting bribes from Doheny.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cabinet member found guilty in Teapot Dome scandal\n|url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/cabinet-member-guilty-in-teapot-dome-scandal |work=On ThisDay In History |publisher=History.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |agency=UPI |title=On This Day: Interior Secretary Fall found guilty in Teapot Dome scandal  |date=October 25, 2019 |url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/10/25/On-This-Day-Interior-Secretary-Fall-found-guilty-in-Teapot-Dome-scandal/4141571969653/}}</ref> Conversely, in 1930, Doheny was acquitted of paying bribes to Fall.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1977/06/09/uncovering-a-coverup-on-teapot-dome/93c16e16-8e32-4bf0-aabd-bb83c9bebd0d/ |title=Uncovering a Coverup on Teapot Dome |author= Chalmers M. Roberts|date= June 9, 1977}}</ref> Further, Doheny's corporation foreclosed on Fall's home<ref>{{cite book |via=Google books |title=Cold Case: The Assassination of Pat Garrett: Investigating History's Mysteries |author=W. C. Jameson | publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2020 |ISBN = 149304589X | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Vi_XDwAAQBAJ |page=204}}</ref> in the [[Tularosa Basin]], New Mexico, because of \"unpaid loans\" that turned out to be that same $100,000 bribe. Sinclair served six months in jail on a charge of [[jury tampering]].<ref>{{cite book |last=McCartney |first=Laton |title=The Teapot Dome Scandal: How Big Oil Bought the Harding White House and Tried to Steal the Country |location=New York |publisher=[[Random House]] |year=2008 |isbn=978-1-4000-6316-1 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/teapotdomescanda00mcca }}</ref>\n\nAlthough Fall was to blame for this scandal, Harding's reputation was sullied because of his involvement with the wrong people. Evidence proving Fall's guilt only arose after Harding's death in 1923.<ref>{{cite book|last1=MacDonald|first1=Scott B.|last2=Hughes|first2=Jane E.|title=Separating Fools from Their Money: A History of American Financial Scandals|orig-year=1st pub. 2007|publisher=Transaction|location=New Brunswick, N.J.|isbn=978-0-7658-0356-6|date=2015|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/separat_mac_2007_00_2620}}</ref>\n\nAnother significant outcome was the Supreme Court's ruling in ''[[McGrain v. Daugherty]]'' (1927) which, for the first time, explicitly established that [[Congress of the United States|Congress]] had the power to compel testimony.<ref name=\"oyez\">{{Cite web | title = McGrain v. Daugherty | publisher = Oyez.org | url = https://www.oyez.org/cases/1901-1939/1924/1924_28 | accessdate = 2 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe oil field was then idled for 49 years, but went back into production in 1976. After earning over $569 million in revenue having extracted {{convert|22|e6oilbbl|lk=in}} of oil over the previous 39 years, in February 2015, the [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] sold the oil field for $45 million to New York-based Stranded Oil Resources Corp.<ref name=revenues>[http://www.denverpost.com/2015/01/30/government-sells-scandalized-teapot-dome-oilfield-for-45-million Government sells scandalized Teapot Dome oilfield for $45 million], ''[[Denver Post]]'', [[Associated Press]]'', January 30, 2015. Retrieved 4 June 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Alleghany Capital Corporation Announces Acquisition Of \"Teapot Dome Oilfield\" By Stranded Oil Resources Corporation |date= January 30, 2015 |author=Alleghany Capital |agency=PR Newswire |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/alleghany-capital-corporation-announces-acquisition-of-teapot-dome-oilfield-by-stranded-oil-resources-corporation-300028515.html}}</ref>\n\n==Comparison==\n\nThe Teapot Dome scandal has historically been regarded as the worst such scandal in the United States \u2013 the \"[[high water mark]]\" of cabinet corruption. It is often used as a benchmark for comparison with subsequent scandals. In particular it has been compared to the [[Watergate scandal]], in which a cabinet member, Attorney General [[John N. Mitchell]], went to prison, the second time in American history that a member of cabinet has been incarcerated.<ref>{{cite book|title=Watergate & the Teapot Dome Scandal: The History and Legacy of America's Most Notorious Government Scandals|date=November 2, 2016|publisher=Charles River Editors |edition=Kindle |asin=B01N9IMB2P}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Uncovering a Coverup on Teapot Dome|last=Roberts|first=Chalmers M.|date=June 9, 1977|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Little Green House on K Street]]\n* [[List of federal political scandals in the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* Bates, J. Leonard. ''The Origins of Teapot Dome''. Urbana, IL: University of Illinois Press, 1963.\n* Bennett, Leslie E. [http://academic.brooklyn.cuny.edu/history/johnson/teapotdome.htm \"One Lesson From History: Appointment of Special Counsel and the Investigation of the Teapot Dome Scandal\"]. Washington, D.C.: Brookings Institution, 1999.\n* Ise, John. ''The United States Oil Policy''. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press, 1926.\n* Murphy, Blakely M. (ed.) ''Conservation of Oil and Gas: A Legal History''. Chicago: Section of Mineral Law, American Bar Association, 1949.\n* [[Burl Noggle|Noggle, Burl]]. ''Teapot Dome: Oil and Politics in the 1920s''. Baton Rouge, LA: Louisiana State University Press, 1962.\n* Werner, M. R. and Starr, John. ''Teapot Dome''. New York: Viking Press, 1959.\n\n{{US federal public corruption law}}\n{{US history}}\n{{Special Prosecutors and Independent Counsels of the U.S.}}\n\n{{coord|43.2885808|N|106.1733516|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Teapot Dome scandal| ]]\n[[Category:Petroleum in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political corruption scandals in the United States]]\n[[Category:1920s in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bribery scandals]]\n[[Category:Cover-ups]]\n[[Category:History of Kern County, California]]\n[[Category:History of the San Joaquin Valley]]\n[[Category:History of Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Natrona County, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Oil fields in Kern County, California]]\n[[Category:Petroleum in California]]\n[[Category:Sinclair Oil Corporation]]\n[[Category:1922 in California]]\n[[Category:1923 in California]]\n[[Category:1922 in Wyoming]]\n[[Category:1923 in Wyoming]]\n", "name_user": "Elinruby", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInvestigation and outcome:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teapot_Dome_scandal"}
{"title_page": "Giles Martin", "text_new": "{{short description|English record producer, songwriter, composer and multi-instrumentalist}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources |date=June 2013}}\n{{External links|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Giles Martin\n|image = Giles Martin.jpg\n|caption = Martin backstage at the show ''LOVE''\n|background = non_performing_personnel\n|birth_name = Giles Martin\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1969|10|9|df=yes}}\n|death_date =\n|Occupation(s) = songwriter\n|years_active =\n|label = C.A. Management\n|Notable_albums = ''[[Pure (Hayley Westenra album)|Pure]]'', ''[[Love (The Beatles album)|Love]]''\n}}\n\n'''Giles Martin''' (born 9 October 1969) is an English record producer, songwriter, composer and multi-instrumentalist. His studio recordings, stage shows, TV and film works have been critically acclaimed and commercially successful around the globe. He is the son of [[The Beatles|Beatles]] producer [[George Martin]] and half-brother of actor [[Gregory Paul Martin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/jun/30/books.guardianreview1|title=Sounds and vision|first=Mark|last=Espiner|work =The Guardian|location=London|date=27 November 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nMartin was educated at [[Stowe School]],<ref name=Stowe>{{cite web|url=https://www.stowe.co.uk/getmedia/93b1ccaf-186b-4c6f-9a3a-578cbef46b1e/The_Column_Issue7|title=The Column - Issue 7 (page 11 - Giles Martin)|work=[[Stowe School]], Buckinghamshire|date=2008|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref> a boarding [[independent school]] in the [[civil parish]] of [[Stowe, Buckinghamshire|Stowe]] in [[Buckinghamshire]], leaving its boarding house, Lyttelton, in 1988,<ref name=Stowe/> followed by the [[University of Manchester]].\n\n==Life and career==\nGiles Martin grew up without much awareness of [[The Beatles]], and was discouraged by his father from pursuing a career in music lest the inevitable comparisons should be made between father and son.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} However, Giles carried on, first playing in the band Velvet Jones, then writing [[jingle]]s in college. In 1995, he was appointed music co-director for the television and radio music countdown show, ''[[The Great Music Experience]]''. He worked on the [[Party at the Palace]] concert to celebrate [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]]'s [[Golden Jubilee]], for which he also produced the subsequent album and DVD.\n\nIn 2004 he produced [[Hayley Westenra]]'s multi-platinum album ''[[Pure (Hayley Westenra album)|Pure]]'', the UK's fastest-selling [[European classical music|classical]] album of all time. Other acts Martin produced include [[Kula Shaker]], [[Jeff Beck]], [[Elvis Costello]], [[INXS]], and [[Kate Bush]].{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\nIn 2006 Martin collaborated with his father to remix, rearrange, and recombine the music of the Beatles into a soundscape for ''[[Love (Cirque du Soleil)|Love]]'', a theatrical production of [[Cirque du Soleil]], which opened at [[The Mirage]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]]. His use of digital music production and manipulation techniques allowed him to create ''Love'''s musical [[Mashup (music)|mash-ups]] which he updated in 2016 for the show's 10th Anniversary. He produced the music for the final Broadway performance of ''[[Rent (musical)|Rent]]'' and worked with [[Martin Scorsese]] on his [[George Harrison]] film documentary ''[[George Harrison: Living in the Material World|Living in the Material World]]''.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}  Further film collaboration includes working with [[Ron Howard]] on his Beatles documentary feature ''[[Eight Days A Week]]'' and the British action franchise [[Kingsman (franchise)|''Kingsman'']]. Martin was music director for the [[Elton John]] bio-pic ''[[Rocketman (film)|Rocketman]]''.\n\nIn 2009 Martin returned to the Beatles' catalogue with ''[[The Beatles: Rock Band]]'', a video game that allows players to simulate performing Beatles songs with plastic instruments. Martin produced the title's music, cleaning and reworking the audio to suit the game's mechanics. In 2013, Martin produced tracks and served as executive producer on [[Paul McCartney|Paul McCartney's]] ''[[New (album)|New]]'' album. He was the producer in charge of the 50th anniversary Beatles remix/deluxe reissue packages of ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', [[The Beatles (album)|the White Album]], and ''[[Abbey Road]]'', released respectively in 2017, 2018, and 2019.\n\nMartin has served as Head of Sound Experience since 2014 at [[Sonos]] Inc., a company that builds wireless home audio systems. In late 2018, Martin was appointed as Head of Audio & Sound of the [[Universal Music Group]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.universalmusic.com/universal-music-group-appoints-giles-martin-head-audio-sound/|title=Universal Music Group Appoints Giles Martin as Head of Audio & Sound - UMG|date=22 October 2018|work=UMG|access-date=25 October 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> The role was specifically created for Martin where he is based at UMG's [[Abbey Road Studios]].\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is married to Melanie Gore-Grimes, with whom he has two children. They live in London, England.\n\n==Awards==\nGiles Martin received two [[Grammy]] awards, both in 2007 for the ''[[Love (The Beatles album)|Love]]'' soundtrack album, as a producer of the Best Compilation Soundtrack Album For Motion Picture, Television Or Other Visual Media and as a surround producer of the Best Surround Sound Album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards|title=Awards|date=30 April 2017|website=GRAMMY.com}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works ==\n* 1994 The K's (also known as [[Kula Shaker]]) (GUT)\n* 1994 [[My Life Story]] (Mother Tongue)\n* 1995 [[The Glory of Gershwin]] (Mercury)\n* 1995 The Choir (BBC)\n* 1995 The Great Music Experience\n* 1995/96 ''[[The Beatles Anthology]]'' ([[EMI]]/[[Apple Corps|Apple]])\n* 1996 Monorail \u2013 Hairdressing (Edel)\n* 1996/97/98 Velvet Jones (Naked)\n* 1996/97 In My Life (Echo/MCA)\n* 2000/01 The Alice Band (Instant Karma/Sony)\n* 2002 Party at the Palace&nbsp;\u2013 Live show, CD and DVD releases (EMI/Virgin)\n* 2003 [[Hayley Westenra]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Pure (Hayley Westenra album)|Pure]]'' (Universal/Decca)\n* 2004 [[Willard White]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''My Way'' (Sony/BMG)\n* 2004/05 Hayley Westenra&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Odyssey (Hayley Westenra album)|Odyssey]]'' (Universal/Decca)\n* 2004/05/06&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Love (Beatles album)|Love]]'' ([[Apple Records|Apple]]/[[Cirque du Soleil]]/MGM/EMI)\n* 2007 [[Kim Richey]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Chinese Boxes'' (Vanguard)\n* 2007 [[Paco Pe\u00f1a]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Requiem''\n* 2008 [[RENT]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Live on Broadway'' (Sony Pictures)\n* 2008/09 [[The Beatles Rock Band]] (MTV Networks)\n* 2009/10/11 ''[[George Harrison: Living in the Material World]]''\n* 2012 [[George Harrison]] - ''[[Early Takes: Volume 1]]'' ([[Universal Music Enterprises|UM<sup>e</sup>]])\n* 2013 [[Paul McCartney]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[New (album)|New]]'' (Hear Music)\n* 2015 The Beatles - ''[[1 (Beatles album)#1+|1+]]'' (Apple)\n* 2016 The Beatles - ''[[The_Beatles_at_the_Hollywood_Bowl#Live_at_the_Hollywood_Bowl|Live at the Hollywood Bowl]]''\n* 2017 The Beatles - ''[[Sgt._Pepper's_Lonely_Hearts_Club_Band#50th_anniversary_editions|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band - 50th anniversary editions]]\n* 2018 The Beatles - ''[[The Beatles (album)]] - 50th anniversary editions\n* 2019 ''[[Rocketman (film)|Rocketman]]'' - music director for [[Elton John]] biopic, directed by [[Dexter Fletcher]]\n* 2019 The Beatles - ''[[Abbey Road]]'' - 50th anniversary editions\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.camanagement.co.uk/roster3.htm Giles Martin \u2013 Management biography]\n*[https://itunes.apple.com/gb/podcast/giles-martin-meet-producer/id726603460?mt=2 Giles talks to Matt Everitt about the Paul McCartney \"NEW\" album]\n*[http://music.guardian.co.uk/pop/alexispetridis/story/0,,1947938,00.html Giles talks to Alexis Petridis about producing \"LOVE\"]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070128132144/http://jobkite.com/lounge/celebrity/beatles.htm Interview with both Martins regarding \"LOVE\"]\n*[http://www.waves.com/Content.aspx?id=3568 Technical article on production, Giles Martin talks to Harvey Kubernik]\n*[http://www.recordproduction.com/giles-martin-record-producer.html Giles Martin video interview]\n*[https://www.npr.org/sections/allsongs/2017/05/23/528678711/why-remix-sgt-peppers-giles-martin-the-man-behind-the-project-explains Giles talks with NPR about the Sgt.Pepper remix]\n*[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/review-the-beatles-sgt-peppers-anniversary-editions-w484397 Rolling Stone Sgt.Pepper remix review]\n*[http://www.avidblogs.com/giles-martin-beatles-eight-days-week-touring-years/ The Beatles Eight Days A Week]\n*[https://www.fastcompany.com/3051594/how-a-beatles-producer-is-helping-sonos-re-imagine-the-way-we-hear-music Giles Martin working with Sonos]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin, Giles}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:English multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:English record producers]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:George Martin]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Stowe School]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English record producer, songwriter, composer and multi-instrumentalist}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources |date=June 2013}}\n{{External links|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Giles Martin\n|image = Giles Martin.jpg\n|caption = Martin backstage at the show ''LOVE''\n|background = non_performing_personnel\n|birth_name = Giles M